1
00:00:53,262 --> 00:00:55,264
(INTRIGUING
WESTERN MUSIC PLAYING)

2
00:01:19,413 --> 00:01:21,040
(MUSIC CRESCENDOS, FADES)

3
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:24,126
(MUSIC PULSES)

4
00:01:28,130 --> 00:01:30,132
(SAILORS SPEAKING GERMAN)

5
00:01:45,731 --> 00:01:47,358
(CAPTAIN IN GERMAN)

6
00:01:47,441 --> 00:01:48,442
MAN: (IN ENGLISH) Uh, Sweden.

7
00:01:48,526 --> 00:01:49,527
(IN GERMAN)

8
00:01:49,610 --> 00:01:51,612
MAN: (IN ENGLISH) I'm... I'm... Swedish

9
00:01:51,696 --> 00:01:53,447
but I speak a little English.

10
00:01:53,531 --> 00:01:54,532
We're coming on board.

11
00:01:54,615 --> 00:01:56,617
(SAILORS SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

12
00:01:58,327 --> 00:02:00,162
(CAPTAIN ORDERING IN GERMAN)

13
00:02:01,831 --> 00:02:04,375
(IN ENGLISH) All are welcome.
All are welcome.

14
00:02:05,001 --> 00:02:08,337
Even the little one. He can come too.

15
00:02:09,380 --> 00:02:10,423
Welcome.

16
00:02:10,506 --> 00:02:12,508
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

17
00:02:15,928 --> 00:02:17,096
Why are you here?

18
00:02:17,805 --> 00:02:19,765
Just a little sailing holiday.

19
00:02:19,849 --> 00:02:21,058
A jolly boys trip.

20
00:02:21,142 --> 00:02:22,143
Take your hands off.

21
00:02:26,647 --> 00:02:28,607
Papers? Passport?

22
00:02:31,152 --> 00:02:32,987
(GRUNTS) Here you go.

23
00:02:38,034 --> 00:02:39,785
Any other people on the boat?

24
00:02:40,828 --> 00:02:41,996
Just the two of us.

25
00:02:43,164 --> 00:02:44,457
(IN GERMAN)

26
00:02:44,540 --> 00:02:45,541
Nein.

27
00:02:46,208 --> 00:02:47,501
(CAPTAIN SPEAKING)

28
00:02:48,336 --> 00:02:49,754
(IN ENGLISH) Come, come,
we have lots to eat...

29
00:02:49,837 --> 00:02:51,672
Take your dirty hands off me!

30
00:02:51,756 --> 00:02:53,049
- (SAILORS SHOUTING IN GERMAN)
- (GUNS COCKING)

31
00:02:53,132 --> 00:02:54,383
CAPTAIN: (IN ENGLISH) Back off!

32
00:02:57,136 --> 00:02:59,472
And you, put your hands in the air!

33
00:03:08,439 --> 00:03:10,441
(LAUGHING)

34
00:03:12,109 --> 00:03:13,694
Ooh! (LAUGHING)

35
00:03:13,778 --> 00:03:15,029
You're in trouble now!

36
00:03:15,112 --> 00:03:17,031
You've been a naughty boy!

37
00:03:19,950 --> 00:03:22,203
I'll give you 100 francs to shoot him.

38
00:03:22,286 --> 00:03:23,245
Don't shoot me!

39
00:03:23,329 --> 00:03:25,206
(BOTH CONTINUE LAUGHING)

40
00:03:25,289 --> 00:03:27,792
He hates Germans.
You should really shoot him.

41
00:03:28,501 --> 00:03:32,046
I... I'm sorry. You are very scary.

42
00:03:32,129 --> 00:03:33,422
MAN: Make him walk the plank.

43
00:03:33,506 --> 00:03:34,882
He loves wood.

44
00:03:34,965 --> 00:03:36,967
(BOTH CONTINUE LAUGHING)

45
00:03:39,011 --> 00:03:41,347
Dirty drunken animal!

46
00:03:42,973 --> 00:03:44,141
Guilty as charged.

47
00:03:44,225 --> 00:03:45,518
(BOTH LAUGHING)

48
00:03:47,353 --> 00:03:49,480
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

49
00:03:49,563 --> 00:03:51,565
- (SAILORS SPEAKING GERMAN)
- (DRAWER RATTLES)

50
00:03:58,781 --> 00:04:00,658
(IN ENGLISH) I always take
a can of kerosene

51
00:04:00,741 --> 00:04:02,827
for just these sort of occasions.

52
00:04:02,910 --> 00:04:03,911
(INHALES)

53
00:04:04,954 --> 00:04:06,288
It's been a while,

54
00:04:06,372 --> 00:04:09,959
but the last time someone laughed at me
when I boarded their vessel,

55
00:04:10,042 --> 00:04:11,669
I gave them the choice.

56
00:04:11,752 --> 00:04:13,546
Either swim to shore

57
00:04:13,629 --> 00:04:16,298
or take their chances on a burning ship.

58
00:04:16,382 --> 00:04:17,383
(LIQUID POURING)

59
00:04:17,466 --> 00:04:21,679
Hans and I wondered
which option they'd choose,

60
00:04:21,762 --> 00:04:24,723
death by water or death by fire.

61
00:04:26,267 --> 00:04:27,435
Oddly, they chose both.

62
00:04:28,185 --> 00:04:29,562
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

63
00:04:33,858 --> 00:04:35,025
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC CONTINUES)

64
00:04:35,109 --> 00:04:36,861
(IN ENGLISH) They waited
until the very last moment,

65
00:04:36,944 --> 00:04:38,612
until their hair was on fire,

66
00:04:40,406 --> 00:04:42,908
and their blistered skin
peeled from their fingers,

67
00:04:43,492 --> 00:04:46,287
before they immersed themselves in water

68
00:04:46,370 --> 00:04:47,830
in the vain hope

69
00:04:47,913 --> 00:04:49,707
of reaching shore.

70
00:04:50,458 --> 00:04:54,170
One of them sank immediately and perished.

71
00:04:54,670 --> 00:04:57,214
But to our amazement, the big one,

72
00:04:58,549 --> 00:04:59,633
he showed great spirit.

73
00:05:01,093 --> 00:05:02,678
In spite of all the odds...

74
00:05:02,761 --> 00:05:03,804
(IN GERMAN)

75
00:05:03,888 --> 00:05:06,015
...he painstakingly made it to shore.

76
00:05:06,098 --> 00:05:08,100
We followed and cheered him on

77
00:05:08,184 --> 00:05:11,020
and rewarded this impressive achievement

78
00:05:12,188 --> 00:05:13,272
with a bullet

79
00:05:14,356 --> 00:05:16,442
to the back of his head.

80
00:05:19,028 --> 00:05:20,362
Isn't that funny?

81
00:05:21,572 --> 00:05:22,573
Why aren't you laughing?

82
00:05:24,283 --> 00:05:26,285
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)
- (SAILORS GRUNT, SCREAM)

83
00:05:26,368 --> 00:05:27,828
(SAILORS CLAMORING)

84
00:05:27,912 --> 00:05:28,996
- (SLASHING)
- (GASPS)

85
00:05:29,872 --> 00:05:31,874
(AMUSING WESTERN MUSIC PLAYING)

86
00:05:36,378 --> 00:05:37,671
- (MAN GRUNTS)
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)

87
00:05:38,964 --> 00:05:40,925
- (GRUNTS)
- (SAILOR 1 SHOUTS IN GERMAN)

88
00:05:42,676 --> 00:05:43,802
- (GUN FIRES QUIETLY)
- (SAILOR 2 YELPS)

89
00:05:43,886 --> 00:05:45,763
- (SAILOR 3 GRUNTS)
- (SAILORS SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

90
00:05:46,597 --> 00:05:47,598
(SAILOR 4 SCREAMS)

91
00:05:47,681 --> 00:05:49,558
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)
- (SAILORS GRUNTING)

92
00:05:50,643 --> 00:05:53,103
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)
- (SAILOR 5 GASPS)

93
00:05:53,187 --> 00:05:54,230
- (SIGHS)
- (SAILOR 6 YELPS)

94
00:05:55,731 --> 00:05:57,733
(GROANING)

95
00:05:59,902 --> 00:06:01,153
- (GROWLS)
- (SAILOR 7 GROANS)

96
00:06:01,237 --> 00:06:03,239
(AMUSING
WESTERN MUSIC CONTINUES)

97
00:06:10,996 --> 00:06:12,540
Nice work, Lassen.

98
00:06:14,250 --> 00:06:15,668
There's more where they came from.

99
00:06:16,460 --> 00:06:17,461
Yes.

100
00:06:18,754 --> 00:06:19,797
(LASSEN GROANS)

101
00:06:22,633 --> 00:06:24,134
(LASSEN GRUNTS)

102
00:06:24,218 --> 00:06:25,219
Ah...

103
00:06:26,887 --> 00:06:28,305
Not sure it's working, Lassen.

104
00:06:29,390 --> 00:06:31,267
The captain looks rather agitated.

105
00:06:36,438 --> 00:06:38,023
They're bringing their guns to bear.

106
00:06:38,524 --> 00:06:39,692
(MISSILE FIRES)

107
00:06:42,736 --> 00:06:44,655
They'll find their range soon, sir.

108
00:06:44,738 --> 00:06:46,907
Freddy, should we be worried?

109
00:06:46,991 --> 00:06:48,492
Oh, I don't think so, sir.

110
00:06:48,576 --> 00:06:51,453
It's a rather large explosive,
so I set a rather large fuse.

111
00:06:51,537 --> 00:06:53,664
I located the outside of the powder room,

112
00:06:53,747 --> 00:06:54,957
so when it goes bang,

113
00:06:55,040 --> 00:06:56,166
it really should go bang.

114
00:06:56,250 --> 00:06:57,209
(MISSILE FIRES)

115
00:06:57,293 --> 00:06:59,086
(EXPLOSION)

116
00:06:59,169 --> 00:07:00,379
Closer...

117
00:07:00,462 --> 00:07:02,298
Should be any second now, chaps.

118
00:07:02,881 --> 00:07:04,883
(SAILORS CLAMORING IN DISTANCE)

119
00:07:07,428 --> 00:07:08,554
Freddy?

120
00:07:08,637 --> 00:07:09,638
(EXPLOSION BOOMING)

121
00:07:14,059 --> 00:07:15,269
Good work, Frederick.

122
00:07:16,061 --> 00:07:17,438
Thank you, Captain.

123
00:07:17,521 --> 00:07:19,690
Now, any chance you can tell us
what we're doing here, sir?

124
00:07:19,773 --> 00:07:20,774
(MUSIC FADES)

125
00:07:21,358 --> 00:07:22,943
(PROJECTOR CLICKING)

126
00:07:24,653 --> 00:07:26,655
(JOLLY ORCHESTRAL MUSIC PLAYING)

127
00:07:29,867 --> 00:07:31,493
NEWSREADER: (ON PROJECTOR)
The war in Europe rages on

128
00:07:31,577 --> 00:07:35,372
as Hitler and his Nazi horde
sweep aside all in their path.

129
00:07:35,456 --> 00:07:38,042
Poland, Belgium and now France

130
00:07:38,125 --> 00:07:41,086
have all fallen
to Hitler's fascist regime,

131
00:07:41,170 --> 00:07:45,382
leaving Britain holding up the final hopes
of liberation for all of Europe.

132
00:07:45,466 --> 00:07:48,177
So, come on, Blighty,
get ready for a fighty.

133
00:07:48,260 --> 00:07:50,137
But we cannot do it alone.

134
00:07:50,220 --> 00:07:54,308
And any hope for our American brothers
to join us from across the Atlantic

135
00:07:54,391 --> 00:07:59,063
remains frustrated by Germany's
secret weapon, the U-boat.

136
00:07:59,146 --> 00:08:03,150
These deadly little submarines
hunt at will in the North Atlantic.

137
00:08:03,233 --> 00:08:06,945
Undetectable, the U-boat
sinks ships indiscriminately,

138
00:08:07,029 --> 00:08:09,740
whether carrying munitions, provisions

139
00:08:09,823 --> 00:08:13,077
or civilians heading
from our companions across the pond.

140
00:08:13,702 --> 00:08:17,748
So long as the U-boats rule the Atlantic,
it remains impossible

141
00:08:17,831 --> 00:08:20,709
for America's brave troops
to reach our shores.

142
00:08:20,793 --> 00:08:23,921
Will Britain be forced
to appease Hitler's plans

143
00:08:24,004 --> 00:08:27,174
or face devastation from his offensive?

144
00:08:27,257 --> 00:08:29,593
London burns and her seas run red,

145
00:08:29,677 --> 00:08:32,638
as bombs from above
and torpedoes from below

146
00:08:32,721 --> 00:08:34,014
grind the Brits down.

147
00:08:34,098 --> 00:08:36,767
And with no defense
against these lethal U-boats,

148
00:08:36,850 --> 00:08:40,896
it appears all hope may be lost
for peace in Europe.

149
00:08:40,979 --> 00:08:42,064
- (MUSIC STOPS)
- (PROJECTOR CLICKS)

150
00:08:43,774 --> 00:08:46,485
The Germans cut off
our supply chain with U-boats,

151
00:08:47,903 --> 00:08:50,280
we cut off the supply chain
to the U-boats.

152
00:08:51,740 --> 00:08:54,243
Through our intelligence agents,
we've found a way.

153
00:08:54,326 --> 00:08:56,328
(INTRIGUING WESTERN
MUSIC PLAYING)

154
00:08:59,540 --> 00:09:00,666
The entire

155
00:09:01,250 --> 00:09:04,628
servicing, repairing, and rearming

156
00:09:04,712 --> 00:09:06,880
of Hitler's Atlantic U-boat fleet...

157
00:09:07,423 --> 00:09:09,508
is operated by two Nazi tug boats...

158
00:09:10,300 --> 00:09:12,886
and an Italian supply ship in Fernando Po.

159
00:09:13,387 --> 00:09:17,516
I need men who are willing
to go and sink those ships.

160
00:09:18,350 --> 00:09:21,729
Why don't we just air-raid Fernando Po
and sink the ships?

161
00:09:21,812 --> 00:09:23,480
(EXHALES)

162
00:09:23,564 --> 00:09:26,817
Because crafty Germans,
being crafty Germans,

163
00:09:28,026 --> 00:09:30,529
have positioned themselves
in a Spanish colony.

164
00:09:30,612 --> 00:09:33,198
Fernando Po is neutral territory.

165
00:09:33,282 --> 00:09:34,992
If we attack that colony,

166
00:09:35,075 --> 00:09:37,619
the rest of unoccupied Europe
will join the Nazis,

167
00:09:37,703 --> 00:09:39,913
and it's only a question of time
before we find ourselves

168
00:09:39,997 --> 00:09:43,041
frying big pink sausages
wearing nothing but lederhosen.

169
00:09:44,585 --> 00:09:48,464
Hitler is not playing by the rules
and neither are we.

170
00:09:49,673 --> 00:09:53,927
This will of course be an unsanctioned,
unauthorized and unofficial mission.

171
00:09:55,929 --> 00:09:58,891
If they're captured by the British,
they'll be thrown in jail.

172
00:10:00,684 --> 00:10:01,935
But if the Nazis find them...

173
00:10:04,688 --> 00:10:05,981
it's torture and death.

174
00:10:07,316 --> 00:10:10,194
MAN: Somewhat contentiously,
I may have just the man,

175
00:10:10,694 --> 00:10:12,279
but rather inconveniently,

176
00:10:12,362 --> 00:10:15,491
he's currently incarcerated
at His Majesty's pleasure.

177
00:10:15,991 --> 00:10:17,743
We may not like his attitude,

178
00:10:17,826 --> 00:10:20,621
but he's bold, he's a killer,

179
00:10:22,623 --> 00:10:24,500
and the men will follow him anywhere.

180
00:10:25,167 --> 00:10:27,336
Are we sure this is a good idea?

181
00:10:29,379 --> 00:10:30,756
Of course we're not.

182
00:10:30,839 --> 00:10:32,132
But we're desperate.

183
00:10:33,425 --> 00:10:35,093
- Send him in.
- (DOOR OPENS)

184
00:10:35,177 --> 00:10:36,178
SERGEANT: Forward!

185
00:10:36,261 --> 00:10:38,263
- (FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)
- (CHAINS CLINKING)

186
00:10:39,640 --> 00:10:40,808
SERGEANT: Stand there, Major.

187
00:10:42,559 --> 00:10:44,853
(INTRIGUING MUSIC CONTINUES)

188
00:10:54,488 --> 00:10:55,489
MAN: Thank you, Sergeant.

189
00:11:00,369 --> 00:11:02,621
Gus March-Phillips,
this is Lieutenant Commander...

190
00:11:02,704 --> 00:11:05,040
Fleming. Ian Fleming.

191
00:11:05,123 --> 00:11:07,751
He used to be at Naval Intelligence,
now he works for me.

192
00:11:10,921 --> 00:11:12,130
Why am I here, M?

193
00:11:12,214 --> 00:11:14,716
I have a mission I want you to lead.

194
00:11:15,342 --> 00:11:17,678
Why are you asking me, M?

195
00:11:17,761 --> 00:11:19,721
Help yourself to a cup of tea, Major.

196
00:11:29,940 --> 00:11:30,941
(GUS CLEARS THROAT)

197
00:11:33,527 --> 00:11:36,822
We both know that I'm...

198
00:11:38,740 --> 00:11:41,743
not very popular with the administration.

199
00:11:42,536 --> 00:11:44,121
M: The reason they find you unattractive

200
00:11:45,038 --> 00:11:47,958
is the very reason I find you attractive.

201
00:11:49,334 --> 00:11:50,335
Mission?

202
00:11:50,419 --> 00:11:51,879
M: Operation Postmaster.

203
00:11:51,962 --> 00:11:54,506
To neutralize the German U-boats
in the North Atlantic.

204
00:11:55,841 --> 00:11:56,967
(RATTLING)

205
00:11:59,052 --> 00:12:01,597
- And, uh, what's the plan?
- (SIGHS)

206
00:12:02,139 --> 00:12:03,891
FLEMING: The U-boats need

207
00:12:03,974 --> 00:12:05,601
- fuel and torpedoes.
- Oh.

208
00:12:05,684 --> 00:12:08,186
But they also need
carbon dioxide filters for oxygen.

209
00:12:09,271 --> 00:12:11,189
Without them, they can't dive
and they can't hunt.

210
00:12:12,441 --> 00:12:14,276
Stuck on the surface, they're obsolete.

211
00:12:18,697 --> 00:12:19,698
Target?

212
00:12:20,240 --> 00:12:21,491
The Duchessa d'Aosta.

213
00:12:22,159 --> 00:12:24,369
She's an Italian ship
the Germans have been using...

214
00:12:24,453 --> 00:12:25,704
(CONTINUES DRAGGING CHAIR)

215
00:12:29,333 --> 00:12:30,709
(FLEMING CLEARS THROAT)

216
00:12:30,792 --> 00:12:34,838
...to refuel, re-arm and replenish
the CO2 filters for the entire fleet.

217
00:12:35,881 --> 00:12:38,550
She's hidden off the coast of West Africa.

218
00:12:38,634 --> 00:12:41,053
A small island called Fernando Po.

219
00:12:41,136 --> 00:12:44,598
We want you to, um, sink her.

220
00:12:44,681 --> 00:12:47,392
M: You'll be posing as fishermen
sailing down the west coast

221
00:12:47,476 --> 00:12:49,603
on board a trawler
loaded with enough explosives

222
00:12:49,686 --> 00:12:50,854
to destroy the Duchessa.

223
00:12:51,480 --> 00:12:53,941
This is Agents Heron and Stewart.

224
00:12:54,024 --> 00:12:55,943
They'll be working
undercover on the island.

225
00:12:56,860 --> 00:13:00,364
Mr. Heron's already established there,
running various businesses.

226
00:13:00,447 --> 00:13:01,573
What businesses?

227
00:13:01,657 --> 00:13:05,369
A casino bar, and illegal exports game.

228
00:13:06,286 --> 00:13:07,537
Profitable?

229
00:13:07,621 --> 00:13:09,414
- I do quite well.
- (LIGHTER CLICKS)

230
00:13:09,498 --> 00:13:12,334
High-ranking Nazis
are my most valued clients.

231
00:13:12,417 --> 00:13:13,752
Good for you.

232
00:13:15,837 --> 00:13:16,838
(LIGHTER CLICKS)

233
00:13:17,339 --> 00:13:19,216
M: Miss Stewart, an actress and singer,

234
00:13:19,299 --> 00:13:21,301
has been training with us
for the last two years.

235
00:13:21,385 --> 00:13:24,012
She'll be posing
as a gold trader from New York.

236
00:13:24,096 --> 00:13:25,889
Her mission is to seduce and distract

237
00:13:25,973 --> 00:13:27,891
the island's
Commanding Officer Heinrich Luhr.

238
00:13:27,975 --> 00:13:30,978
She's very capable and somewhat motivated.

239
00:13:31,812 --> 00:13:33,188
Motivated how, sir?

240
00:13:33,939 --> 00:13:35,941
My mother's side were German Jews.

241
00:13:37,192 --> 00:13:38,443
They were the first to go.

242
00:13:38,527 --> 00:13:40,112
Very sorry to hear that.

243
00:13:40,195 --> 00:13:41,738
I'm sure you'll recover.

244
00:13:41,822 --> 00:13:45,534
M: We have 44 days
before the Nazis move their operation.

245
00:13:45,617 --> 00:13:46,702
We won't find them again.

246
00:13:50,247 --> 00:13:52,374
If I'm to do this, I'll need my own team.

247
00:13:53,208 --> 00:13:55,460
You won't like them. They're all, uh...

248
00:13:58,171 --> 00:13:59,172
mad.

249
00:13:59,798 --> 00:14:02,634
They'll need to be. Give us their names.

250
00:14:06,596 --> 00:14:07,597
Henry Hayes.

251
00:14:07,681 --> 00:14:11,435
A smart, young Irishman
who hates the Nazis

252
00:14:11,518 --> 00:14:14,771
because his older brother,
who was a close friend of mine,

253
00:14:14,855 --> 00:14:17,816
drowned after a U-boat
sank his fishing trawler.

254
00:14:17,899 --> 00:14:20,318
I've taken him under my wing ever since.

255
00:14:20,402 --> 00:14:22,904
He's cunning, quiet and wily.

256
00:14:22,988 --> 00:14:24,197
More to the point,

257
00:14:24,281 --> 00:14:27,325
Hayes is a magnificent sailor
and I trust him.

258
00:14:28,535 --> 00:14:30,996
If we're going
to try and sink a large ship,

259
00:14:31,079 --> 00:14:33,707
we'll need Freddy "The Buzz" frogman.

260
00:14:34,207 --> 00:14:37,377
He can swim across the channel
with his feet tied together.

261
00:14:37,461 --> 00:14:40,589
Admittedly, he's a convicted arsonist
and a terrible misery

262
00:14:40,672 --> 00:14:42,340
unless he's destroying something.

263
00:14:42,924 --> 00:14:45,385
But he's very good at blowing things up.

264
00:14:46,803 --> 00:14:49,222
Next, we'll need the Danish hammer.

265
00:14:50,432 --> 00:14:51,725
Anders Lassen.

266
00:14:51,808 --> 00:14:55,187
Grew up wrestling bears
and hunting elk on his family estate.

267
00:14:55,270 --> 00:14:58,440
He's a legend with a Bowie knife
and a bow and arrow.

268
00:14:58,523 --> 00:15:00,734
He ran away at 18 to fight the Nazis

269
00:15:00,817 --> 00:15:03,320
after the Gestapo tortured
his brother to death.

270
00:15:03,403 --> 00:15:06,615
He gave up filleting game
for gutting Nazis.

271
00:15:06,698 --> 00:15:09,951
He then turned up on our shores
ready to fight alongside us.

272
00:15:10,035 --> 00:15:12,204
He is an uncontrollable mad dog

273
00:15:12,287 --> 00:15:15,499
who knows a hundred creative ways
to kill a man.

274
00:15:16,583 --> 00:15:17,584
And finally,

275
00:15:17,667 --> 00:15:21,338
and most importantly,
we'll need Geoffrey Apple yard.

276
00:15:22,172 --> 00:15:24,674
Yes, we thought you might.

277
00:15:25,217 --> 00:15:26,802
That's why we sent him

278
00:15:26,885 --> 00:15:28,595
on a reconnaissance mission
to Fernando Po.

279
00:15:28,678 --> 00:15:30,931
Unfortunately,
the Nazis nabbed him on his return.

280
00:15:31,014 --> 00:15:34,434
All the more reason.
He knows what we need to know.

281
00:15:35,519 --> 00:15:36,812
He's a master planner,

282
00:15:36,895 --> 00:15:40,315
a master survivor, a chess grand master

283
00:15:40,398 --> 00:15:42,067
and a surgeon with the blade.

284
00:15:44,569 --> 00:15:47,823
We spent two weeks together
in a Dunkirk foxhole

285
00:15:48,490 --> 00:15:51,952
and if it wasn't for Apple,
I would still be there today.

286
00:15:53,703 --> 00:15:54,788
No Apple, no mission.

287
00:15:55,580 --> 00:15:56,915
I'm afraid that's impossible.

288
00:15:56,998 --> 00:15:57,999
Why?

289
00:15:58,083 --> 00:16:02,796
M: Because he's being held
by an entire German garrison on La Palma.

290
00:16:02,879 --> 00:16:04,506
(HUFFS, LAUGHS)

291
00:16:05,799 --> 00:16:07,217
La Palma's on the way.

292
00:16:07,300 --> 00:16:08,343
(MARJORIE SCOFFS)

293
00:16:08,426 --> 00:16:10,720
- That's insanity.
- You let me worry about that.

294
00:16:14,432 --> 00:16:16,726
I must get me one of those coats.

295
00:16:20,397 --> 00:16:22,399
(AMUSING WESTERN MUSIC PLAYING)

296
00:16:38,874 --> 00:16:40,625
(LAUGHING)

297
00:16:44,129 --> 00:16:46,548
Now, any chance you can tell us
what we're doing here, sir?

298
00:16:46,631 --> 00:16:49,050
Dry yourself off, frogman,
and I'll tell you.

299
00:16:49,134 --> 00:16:51,261
The curiosity is eating us all up, sir.

300
00:16:55,432 --> 00:16:57,851
GUS: I apologize
for all the secrecy, chaps.

301
00:16:57,934 --> 00:17:00,395
But this is an unsanctioned,

302
00:17:01,104 --> 00:17:02,105
unofficial

303
00:17:03,064 --> 00:17:04,691
and unauthorized mission.

304
00:17:05,358 --> 00:17:08,153
If we're picked up by the Brits,
we will all go to jail.

305
00:17:10,030 --> 00:17:12,782
If we're picked up by the Germans,
torture and death.

306
00:17:14,951 --> 00:17:17,746
- So, it's just the four of us then?
- And Captain Apple yard.

307
00:17:18,496 --> 00:17:20,498
He's responsible
for securing this information.

308
00:17:21,416 --> 00:17:23,627
He is, however, in a spot of bother.

309
00:17:24,628 --> 00:17:27,464
He is being held
by the Germans on La Palma.

310
00:17:27,547 --> 00:17:29,049
Our first job is to liberate him.

311
00:17:29,132 --> 00:17:30,592
- Oh, so, that's all, is it?
- GUS: No.

312
00:17:30,675 --> 00:17:32,636
We need to confirm
Apple yard's intelligence.

313
00:17:32,719 --> 00:17:34,429
That's why there are two more agents

314
00:17:34,512 --> 00:17:37,057
on their way to Fernando Po by train,
as we speak.

315
00:17:37,140 --> 00:17:38,892
Doing what, exactly?

316
00:17:38,975 --> 00:17:42,145
They'll be ensuring that those ships
are filled with supplies,

317
00:17:42,229 --> 00:17:44,397
so they're worth blowing up
in the first place.

318
00:17:46,274 --> 00:17:48,944
(TRAIN HORN BLARING)

319
00:17:49,027 --> 00:17:51,321
MARJORIE: It's one thing
taking over the world,

320
00:17:52,030 --> 00:17:54,074
but do they have to
take over the kitchen too?

321
00:17:55,242 --> 00:17:58,161
It's all sausage, cabbage and black bread.

322
00:17:58,703 --> 00:18:00,163
HERON: Who would you have preferred?

323
00:18:00,664 --> 00:18:04,292
MARJORIE: The French offer
the refined classical take.

324
00:18:04,376 --> 00:18:07,504
Côte de boeuf, from age, le beurre...

325
00:18:08,046 --> 00:18:09,547
- ça suffit!
- (MEN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

326
00:18:10,131 --> 00:18:13,051
What about the rustic
spontaneity of the Italians?

327
00:18:14,511 --> 00:18:18,807
Their oils, the linguine, the tomatoes.

328
00:18:18,890 --> 00:18:21,601
I'd climb over the linguine
to get to the fettucine.

329
00:18:21,685 --> 00:18:23,770
But the cinghiale.

330
00:18:23,853 --> 00:18:24,854
MARJORIE: Mmm.

331
00:18:25,730 --> 00:18:27,691
You have me with the wild boar.

332
00:18:28,900 --> 00:18:32,654
But then again, the Spanish offer
the smorgasbord

333
00:18:32,737 --> 00:18:35,532
of the regional paella and tapas.

334
00:18:36,199 --> 00:18:38,451
And jamón ibérico Andalucía.

335
00:18:39,494 --> 00:18:40,495
So?

336
00:18:41,496 --> 00:18:43,415
We're between a rock and a hard place.

337
00:18:43,999 --> 00:18:47,085
If the Brits win the war,
we're stuck with fish and chips.

338
00:18:47,961 --> 00:18:52,299
If the Germans win the war,
we're stuck with this menu.

339
00:18:53,466 --> 00:18:54,467
So?

340
00:18:55,927 --> 00:18:57,846
We'll have the sausage, the cabbage

341
00:18:58,513 --> 00:18:59,806
- and the black bread please.
- (SIGHS)

342
00:19:01,141 --> 00:19:02,142
Très bien. Merci.

343
00:19:06,938 --> 00:19:09,274
(SOLDIERS LAUGHING,
SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

344
00:19:14,112 --> 00:19:15,113
(EXHALES)

345
00:19:19,534 --> 00:19:20,535
Our situation?

346
00:19:21,578 --> 00:19:22,829
Steady.

347
00:19:26,958 --> 00:19:28,752
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATION)

348
00:19:30,712 --> 00:19:32,255
(EXCITING MUSIC PLAYING)

349
00:19:32,339 --> 00:19:33,590
Steady.

350
00:19:34,507 --> 00:19:35,675
(EXHALES)

351
00:19:40,388 --> 00:19:41,431
Now.

352
00:19:48,146 --> 00:19:50,690
(SOLDIERS SPEAKING GERMAN
INDISTINCTLY, LAUGHING)

353
00:19:51,858 --> 00:19:54,778
(IN GERMAN)

354
00:19:54,861 --> 00:19:55,862
MARJORIE: Mmm.

355
00:20:02,702 --> 00:20:03,870
(IN ENGLISH) I'm exhausted.

356
00:20:03,953 --> 00:20:06,664
(IN GERMAN)

357
00:20:07,832 --> 00:20:09,167
- (LAUGHING STOPS)
- (MUSIC FADES)

358
00:20:14,172 --> 00:20:15,173
- (CHUCKLES)
- (SOLDIERS SHUSHING)

359
00:20:18,385 --> 00:20:19,386
(GULPS)

360
00:20:24,557 --> 00:20:26,393
Entschuldigung, bitte.

361
00:20:27,143 --> 00:20:29,229
(EXCITING MUSIC PLAYING)

362
00:20:32,399 --> 00:20:34,109
(SOLDIERS SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

363
00:20:34,984 --> 00:20:35,985
OFFICER: (IN ENGLISH) Halt!

364
00:20:36,069 --> 00:20:37,070
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

365
00:20:37,153 --> 00:20:38,363
(CHATTER STOPS)

366
00:20:40,657 --> 00:20:42,200
(IN GERMAN)

367
00:20:52,085 --> 00:20:53,294
(IN ENGLISH) Is there a problem?

368
00:20:53,795 --> 00:20:55,630
(IN GERMAN)

369
00:21:03,972 --> 00:21:05,807
(IN ENGLISH) I can manage
myself, thank you.

370
00:21:07,058 --> 00:21:08,143
(IN GERMAN)

371
00:21:09,185 --> 00:21:10,603
(IN ENGLISH) Allow me, Miss Stewart.

372
00:21:10,687 --> 00:21:11,896
(MUSIC FADES)

373
00:21:21,614 --> 00:21:23,950
(IN GERMAN)

374
00:21:24,826 --> 00:21:26,161
(IN ENGLISH) Allow me.

375
00:21:26,828 --> 00:21:27,829
Thank you.

376
00:21:27,912 --> 00:21:30,290
(EXCITING MUSIC PLAYING)

377
00:21:30,373 --> 00:21:31,374
SOLDIER: Prost!

378
00:21:31,458 --> 00:21:33,126
(SOLDIERS SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

379
00:21:34,419 --> 00:21:36,421
(EXCITING MUSIC CONTINUES)

380
00:21:47,682 --> 00:21:48,683
HERON: Door.

381
00:21:49,893 --> 00:21:50,894
Locked.

382
00:21:57,775 --> 00:21:59,152
HERON: Case?

383
00:21:59,235 --> 00:22:00,361
Working on it.

384
00:22:00,445 --> 00:22:01,779
(UNLOCKS CASE)

385
00:22:13,583 --> 00:22:15,585
(SOLDIERS SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

386
00:22:19,839 --> 00:22:21,132
(DIAL CLICKING)

387
00:22:21,216 --> 00:22:23,009
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

388
00:22:24,385 --> 00:22:25,553
(SIGNAL BEEPING)

389
00:22:25,637 --> 00:22:26,763
OPERATOR: Sir, contact.

390
00:22:28,848 --> 00:22:30,141
- (SIGNAL BEEPING)
- Contact.

391
00:22:30,892 --> 00:22:31,976
Standing by.

392
00:22:37,106 --> 00:22:38,399
MARJORIE: Duchessa's manifest. Ready?

393
00:22:39,067 --> 00:22:41,402
- Ready.
- 400 B-grade torpedoes. Check.

394
00:22:41,486 --> 00:22:43,071
(EXCITING MUSIC PLAYING)

395
00:22:43,154 --> 00:22:44,322
(SIGNAL BEEPING)

396
00:22:44,405 --> 00:22:46,199
OPERATOR: 400 B-grade torpedoes.

397
00:22:46,282 --> 00:22:47,408
M: Check.

398
00:22:47,492 --> 00:22:48,451
Check.

399
00:22:48,535 --> 00:22:50,328
MARJORIE: 5,000 tons of diesel. Check.

400
00:22:50,411 --> 00:22:51,496
(CLICKING)

401
00:22:52,956 --> 00:22:54,082
(SIGNAL BEEPING)

402
00:22:54,165 --> 00:22:55,917
OPERATOR: 5,000 tons of diesel.

403
00:22:56,000 --> 00:22:57,001
- Lieutenant.
- OPERATOR: Yes, sir?

404
00:22:57,085 --> 00:22:58,253
M: Check.

405
00:22:58,336 --> 00:22:59,796
- (SIGNAL BEEPING)
- HERON: Check.

406
00:22:59,879 --> 00:23:02,006
10,000 carbon dioxide filters. Check.

407
00:23:02,090 --> 00:23:03,841
(SOLDIERS SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

408
00:23:04,551 --> 00:23:06,177
End of message from Stork, sir.

409
00:23:06,761 --> 00:23:07,720
Confirm receipt.

410
00:23:07,804 --> 00:23:09,430
(SIGNAL BEEPING)

411
00:23:09,514 --> 00:23:10,515
HERON: Receipt confirmed.

412
00:23:10,598 --> 00:23:11,849
Urgent, Chequers.

413
00:23:11,933 --> 00:23:13,977
Get the car ready. Inform Fleming.

414
00:23:14,477 --> 00:23:15,562
Let's pack it up.

415
00:23:16,938 --> 00:23:19,816
No point robbing the bank
if there's no gold in the vault.

416
00:23:19,899 --> 00:23:21,901
(EXCITING MUSIC CONTINUES)

417
00:23:23,987 --> 00:23:25,989
(SOLDIERS CONVERSING, LAUGHING)

418
00:23:26,739 --> 00:23:27,740
Thank you.

419
00:23:27,824 --> 00:23:31,160
It's truly comforting to know there's
at least one gentleman in the world.

420
00:23:32,245 --> 00:23:33,997
SOLDIER: Ah! (SPEAKING GERMAN) Idiot!

421
00:23:34,080 --> 00:23:35,248
(HERON, IN GERMAN)

422
00:23:37,250 --> 00:23:38,585
(IN ENGLISH) Good day.

423
00:23:49,470 --> 00:23:50,471
(MUSIC FADES)

424
00:23:52,015 --> 00:23:56,436
Sausage, cabbage and black bread.

425
00:23:59,522 --> 00:24:00,565
(SIGHS)

426
00:24:02,525 --> 00:24:05,445
MAN: Hitler has made us an offer.
An appeasement.

427
00:24:05,528 --> 00:24:07,238
But we must step down our army,

428
00:24:07,322 --> 00:24:10,533
surrender our Navy and accept Nazi rule.

429
00:24:10,617 --> 00:24:15,955
Otherwise, he promises total destruction
of Britain and her empire.

430
00:24:16,456 --> 00:24:20,585
Our best option
is to take Hitler's deal while we can.

431
00:24:22,128 --> 00:24:23,421
The Air Marshal agrees.

432
00:24:24,047 --> 00:24:28,176
He has more bombs,
more men, more machines.

433
00:24:28,760 --> 00:24:30,720
We won't survive much longer.

434
00:24:30,803 --> 00:24:33,931
You have to make
the only decision you can make

435
00:24:34,015 --> 00:24:35,767
in good conscience, Prime Minister.

436
00:24:35,850 --> 00:24:38,019
CHURCHILL: Good God, girls.
Listen to yourselves.

437
00:24:38,102 --> 00:24:39,937
It's not appeasement, it's surrender.

438
00:24:40,521 --> 00:24:43,066
You still fail to realize
who we're up against.

439
00:24:43,149 --> 00:24:46,194
With respect, Prime Minister,
it's you who doesn't realize.

440
00:24:46,903 --> 00:24:48,529
We cannot hope to defeat him.

441
00:24:50,031 --> 00:24:53,242
Hitler is the mainspring of evil,

442
00:24:53,910 --> 00:24:54,994
a guttersnipe.

443
00:24:55,078 --> 00:24:57,080
This is not a man
that we can negotiate with.

444
00:24:57,163 --> 00:24:59,040
I've read his book, Admiral Pound.

445
00:24:59,123 --> 00:25:02,085
The man is a vicious,
victimized ideologue.

446
00:25:02,168 --> 00:25:03,252
He cannot be trusted.

447
00:25:06,005 --> 00:25:08,174
If I thought that we could've achieved
peace through surrendering,

448
00:25:08,257 --> 00:25:09,425
I'd have done it already.

449
00:25:10,051 --> 00:25:12,470
We need to stop our country from starving.

450
00:25:12,553 --> 00:25:16,099
We need three million tons of supplies
to cross the Atlantic every month.

451
00:25:17,183 --> 00:25:19,602
We are currently losing
50% of that to U-boat attacks.

452
00:25:19,686 --> 00:25:21,854
Another reason to take the deal.

453
00:25:22,438 --> 00:25:24,774
I've not finished, Algernon, darling.

454
00:25:26,067 --> 00:25:27,318
We need the Americans,

455
00:25:27,819 --> 00:25:31,572
and they will never enter the war
if we already appear to be a losing side.

456
00:25:31,656 --> 00:25:36,077
Ending hostilities with Germany
is the best path out of this mess.

457
00:25:36,160 --> 00:25:39,205
We are all in agreement, Prime Minister.

458
00:25:40,415 --> 00:25:41,416
Thank you, gentlemen.

459
00:25:45,795 --> 00:25:46,879
(STERNLY) Yes, thank you, gentlemen!

460
00:25:46,963 --> 00:25:48,464
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

461
00:25:51,759 --> 00:25:52,844
(DOOR OPENS)

462
00:25:52,927 --> 00:25:54,929
CHURCHILL: M, Fleming,
this better be good news.

463
00:25:55,012 --> 00:25:58,099
M: Prime Minister,
we have the manifest here, sir.

464
00:25:58,182 --> 00:26:01,144
It's been confirmed the Duchessa
is fully laden with supplies

465
00:26:01,227 --> 00:26:03,646
to keep the U-boats
operational indefinitely.

466
00:26:03,730 --> 00:26:06,941
If we're going to sink her,
now is the time.

467
00:26:07,525 --> 00:26:08,901
They're on their way.

468
00:26:10,236 --> 00:26:11,362
And their chances?

469
00:26:11,446 --> 00:26:14,532
Well, if anyone can, they can.

470
00:26:18,870 --> 00:26:22,790
But if we're discovered,
parliament will remove you from office.

471
00:26:24,584 --> 00:26:25,585
Well,

472
00:26:26,753 --> 00:26:28,546
we'd better make sure
we're not discovered then.

473
00:26:28,629 --> 00:26:30,131
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC FADES)

474
00:26:32,008 --> 00:26:35,511
We'll take it from the Cliffside.
It's an 85-foot sheer climb.

475
00:26:35,595 --> 00:26:38,222
No one should notice
a small, innocuous fishing vessel.

476
00:26:38,806 --> 00:26:40,725
We'll set up in the woods
and see what we're up against,

477
00:26:41,392 --> 00:26:42,643
then we'll go for a night raid.

478
00:26:43,269 --> 00:26:46,147
Slip in quietly,
find Apple, come out fast.

479
00:26:46,647 --> 00:26:47,648
Numbers?

480
00:26:47,732 --> 00:26:50,526
Intelligence suggests
a garrison of 50 to 60.

481
00:26:51,778 --> 00:26:53,404
That should be about 15 each.

482
00:26:53,488 --> 00:26:57,074
Lassen, try not to be greedy.
You do have a reputation.

483
00:26:57,158 --> 00:26:58,910
My killing days are over.

484
00:26:59,535 --> 00:27:01,871
I'm just here as a peacekeeping observer.

485
00:27:01,954 --> 00:27:03,456
(MEN CHUCKLE)

486
00:27:03,956 --> 00:27:06,667
Freddy, bag the kit, silence the weapons.

487
00:27:06,751 --> 00:27:08,753
(EXCITING MUSIC PLAYING)

488
00:27:19,514 --> 00:27:20,932
(SEAGULL SQUAWKING)

489
00:27:21,808 --> 00:27:22,809
(GUN COCKS)

490
00:27:40,868 --> 00:27:42,870
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

491
00:27:46,582 --> 00:27:48,584
(SOLDIERS SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

492
00:27:51,170 --> 00:27:52,672
FREDDY: When do we go?

493
00:27:52,755 --> 00:27:53,840
GUS: 0200.

494
00:27:54,423 --> 00:27:57,134
Take the towers first,
then move onto the radio room,

495
00:27:57,218 --> 00:27:59,595
barracks and end up in the control room...

496
00:28:01,389 --> 00:28:03,307
- (DOG BARKS IN THE DISTANCE)
- What do we have here?

497
00:28:03,933 --> 00:28:05,309
Gestapo.

498
00:28:05,393 --> 00:28:06,394
How'd you know?

499
00:28:06,477 --> 00:28:08,938
GUS: The badder they are,
the better they're dressed.

500
00:28:10,022 --> 00:28:12,066
I really must get me one of those coats.

501
00:28:12,149 --> 00:28:13,943
They must be here for Apple.

502
00:28:15,152 --> 00:28:17,905
It's either torture
or, uh, extraction, sir.

503
00:28:17,989 --> 00:28:20,324
GUS: If they extract him,
it'll be the end of Apple.

504
