I'd hate to see you love.

752
00:42:23,792 --> 00:42:26,378
You don't have to worry about that,

753
00:42:26,461 --> 00:42:27,838
you're too pretty for me.

754
00:42:28,547 --> 00:42:30,382
Freddy, on the other hand...

755
00:42:31,758 --> 00:42:33,510
You'd have to catch me first.

756
00:42:34,219 --> 00:42:35,554
I do love to hunt.

757
00:42:36,763 --> 00:42:37,931
You'd be lucky.

758
00:42:38,682 --> 00:42:40,016
I'm really getting quite hot.

759
00:42:40,100 --> 00:42:42,978
Anyway, my suggestion is
that we take this wider route.

760
00:42:43,061 --> 00:42:45,564
It's obviously longer but it should avoid
any awkward conversations

761
00:42:45,647 --> 00:42:48,400
with German U-boats or British warships.

762
00:42:48,483 --> 00:42:51,361
Weather-dependent,
we should make it there in 15 days.

763
00:42:52,446 --> 00:42:53,447
Agreed.

764
00:42:53,530 --> 00:42:55,574
Haysey, do you think
you could manage that?

765
00:42:56,450 --> 00:42:57,451
Leave it to me, sir.

766
00:42:57,534 --> 00:42:59,536
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

767
00:43:12,716 --> 00:43:14,718
(PEOPLE LAUGHING,
SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

768
00:43:20,223 --> 00:43:21,224
- (MAN SHOUTS)
- (MUSIC FADES)

769
00:43:21,308 --> 00:43:22,893
Just do as you're told

770
00:43:22,976 --> 00:43:24,519
- and get me another drink!
- (GLASSES CLINK)

771
00:43:24,603 --> 00:43:25,687
MAN: Captain, sir.

772
00:43:25,771 --> 00:43:27,022
Can I get you something to eat?

773
00:43:27,105 --> 00:43:28,106
May I... Come this way.

774
00:43:28,190 --> 00:43:29,566
- (OBJECTS CLATTERING)
- Take your hands off me.

775
00:43:29,649 --> 00:43:31,193
(CAPTAIN EXHALES)

776
00:43:32,402 --> 00:43:33,403
You know,

777
00:43:34,905 --> 00:43:35,906
I like you, Femi.

778
00:43:37,824 --> 00:43:40,911
But you touch me again
and you're going to jail.

779
00:43:40,994 --> 00:43:41,995
Femi.

780
00:43:44,080 --> 00:43:45,832
(CHATTER CONTINUES)

781
00:43:47,250 --> 00:43:48,251
I'll deal with him.

782
00:43:49,252 --> 00:43:50,629
Please take care of Miss Stewart.

783
00:43:53,256 --> 00:43:55,342
You know what you need, Captain Binea?

784
00:43:55,425 --> 00:43:56,426
I know what I need.

785
00:43:57,260 --> 00:44:00,180
But do you, Ricardo?

786
00:44:01,598 --> 00:44:03,225
You need another drink.

787
00:44:06,061 --> 00:44:08,522
Marty, good stuff.

788
00:44:08,605 --> 00:44:11,233
Ricardo, that's why I love you.

789
00:44:11,900 --> 00:44:13,318
- You understand.
- (GLASS CLINKS)

790
00:44:14,194 --> 00:44:15,570
HERON: This is Fernando Po.

791
00:44:16,738 --> 00:44:17,906
Everybody's welcome.

792
00:44:19,074 --> 00:44:21,159
Sí... Everybody.

793
00:44:22,452 --> 00:44:23,870
Too many body I think.

794
00:44:23,954 --> 00:44:25,372
(MAN LAUGHING)

795
00:44:27,916 --> 00:44:29,084
Armando?

796
00:44:30,377 --> 00:44:32,462
Have you fallen out with our new friends?

797
00:44:32,546 --> 00:44:34,339
(SIGHS) It's not fair, Ricardo.

798
00:44:35,215 --> 00:44:36,591
This is my harbor.

799
00:44:37,509 --> 00:44:39,010
I am in charge.

800
00:44:39,094 --> 00:44:40,637
Are they stepping on your toes?

801
00:44:40,720 --> 00:44:43,765
They don't step, they stamp!
They tell Captain Binea nothing.

802
00:44:43,849 --> 00:44:44,891
(CHATTER STOPS)

803
00:44:47,644 --> 00:44:50,438
Only now do I hear the Duchessa
is leaving the harbor early.

804
00:44:50,522 --> 00:44:52,148
(CHATTER RESUMES)

805
00:44:53,024 --> 00:44:54,192
Well, good riddance.

806
00:44:55,318 --> 00:44:57,028
The harbor will be yours again.

807
00:44:59,072 --> 00:45:01,449
When will you be free of that ugly vessel?

808
00:45:02,284 --> 00:45:03,493
Three days earlier.

809
00:45:04,828 --> 00:45:06,705
Then we should have another drink.

810
00:45:07,747 --> 00:45:09,749
To celebrate. Marty...

811
00:45:09,833 --> 00:45:11,918
Another round for our Harbor Master.

812
00:45:13,295 --> 00:45:16,423
So, Captain, do you know
where they wish to relocate?

813
00:45:16,965 --> 00:45:20,385
It's neither cat nor dog
that kills for fun,

814
00:45:21,428 --> 00:45:23,513
it's the vixen, not another.

815
00:45:24,639 --> 00:45:28,852
There's only two that kill for fun,
my pretty friend,

816
00:45:29,436 --> 00:45:32,480
the fox and his human brother.

817
00:45:32,564 --> 00:45:34,482
- (LAUGHING)
- (MARJORIE CHUCKLES)

818
00:45:49,164 --> 00:45:51,583
I believe I have
resolved your little riddle.

819
00:45:53,335 --> 00:45:55,921
Chapeau. You play well.

820
00:45:56,004 --> 00:45:57,547
(TAPPING)

821
00:45:59,132 --> 00:46:00,884
Speaking of foxes,

822
00:46:02,218 --> 00:46:05,555
Horowitz and Meyer, West 47th Street.

823
00:46:06,306 --> 00:46:07,807
Have you heard of them?

824
00:46:08,600 --> 00:46:09,893
I don't believe I have, no.

825
00:46:11,102 --> 00:46:12,103
(LIGHTER CLINKS)

826
00:46:17,067 --> 00:46:18,193
(CHATTER FADES)

827
00:46:36,795 --> 00:46:38,046
(LIGHTER CLINKS SOFTLY)

828
00:46:43,802 --> 00:46:45,220
They're the largest gold traders

829
00:46:45,303 --> 00:46:46,554
in Midtown New York

830
00:46:47,180 --> 00:46:48,682
and you haven't heard of them?

831
00:46:49,808 --> 00:46:51,476
I'm afraid I haven't, no.

832
00:46:53,770 --> 00:46:56,064
I am familiar, of course,
with Horowitz and Haim.

833
00:46:56,147 --> 00:46:58,483
But they're in the west side of the city.

834
00:47:01,111 --> 00:47:04,280
But then again, I'm sure you already
knew that, didn't you?

835
00:47:10,662 --> 00:47:11,663
I'm curious,

836
00:47:12,998 --> 00:47:15,250
how do you find dealing with the Jew?

837
00:47:16,418 --> 00:47:17,919
Oh, dear. (CHUCKLES)

838
00:47:18,628 --> 00:47:21,423
I've slipped from one snare
only to find myself in another.

839
00:47:23,299 --> 00:47:24,384
How shall I put this?

840
00:47:25,176 --> 00:47:26,261
I fear your brilliant leader

841
00:47:26,344 --> 00:47:28,888
has mischaracterized
the ancient tribe of Yehudah.

842
00:47:29,597 --> 00:47:30,598
Their ability to not only

843
00:47:30,682 --> 00:47:33,393
survive 3,000 years
with a boot on their neck,

844
00:47:33,476 --> 00:47:35,645
but to prosper in spite of it...

845
00:47:36,771 --> 00:47:39,858
I suspect it inspired
satanic jealousy within him.

846
00:47:40,775 --> 00:47:42,068
In conclusion,

847
00:47:42,819 --> 00:47:44,154
it looks as though

848
00:47:44,237 --> 00:47:47,032
the lady doth protest too much.

849
00:47:51,619 --> 00:47:54,622
Is there a cherry to go
on this blasphemous cake,

850
00:47:54,706 --> 00:47:55,874
or have you finished?

851
00:47:55,957 --> 00:47:57,584
(LAUGHS)

852
00:47:57,667 --> 00:47:59,210
(TAPPING)

853
00:48:00,587 --> 00:48:01,921
I must confess,

854
00:48:03,048 --> 00:48:05,592
not only do I respect
and admire the Jew...

855
00:48:08,386 --> 00:48:09,554
I am one.

856
00:48:09,637 --> 00:48:11,639
(TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

857
00:48:15,143 --> 00:48:16,978
(LAUGHING)

858
00:48:25,528 --> 00:48:27,530
- (LAUGHING)
- (TENSE MUSIC FADES)

859
00:48:29,866 --> 00:48:30,992
(LAUGHING)

860
00:48:31,076 --> 00:48:32,077
MARJORIE: Kidding!

861
00:48:33,745 --> 00:48:34,871
They're greedy rats.

862
00:48:38,750 --> 00:48:41,920
I think this could be
the beginning of a beautiful friendship.

863
00:48:43,546 --> 00:48:46,007
Then I shall throw a party to celebrate.

864
00:48:46,091 --> 00:48:47,967
I don't care for parties.

865
00:48:48,051 --> 00:48:51,137
Oh, spoilsport! Everybody loves a party.

866
00:48:51,679 --> 00:48:53,890
(TENSE WESTERN MUSIC PLAYING)

867
00:48:53,973 --> 00:48:57,143
The Duchessa's leaving
three days earlier than we thought.

868
00:48:57,227 --> 00:49:00,939
If we don't tell the Maid Honor,
they'll arrive too late.

869
00:49:10,115 --> 00:49:11,407
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

870
00:49:11,491 --> 00:49:12,659
OPERATOR: Incoming.

871
00:49:12,742 --> 00:49:14,119
(SIGNAL BEEPING)

872
00:49:14,202 --> 00:49:15,203
Contact.

873
00:49:16,538 --> 00:49:18,748
MARJORIE: More Jerries
on the island than expected.

874
00:49:20,041 --> 00:49:23,461
Tin of corned beef's out of pantry
three days early.

875
00:49:23,545 --> 00:49:24,796
(SIGNAL BEEPING)

876
00:49:27,465 --> 00:49:28,466
I'll take that.

877
00:49:28,550 --> 00:49:30,093
OPERATOR: It's confidential,
sir. For M only.

878
00:49:32,512 --> 00:49:34,722
When it comes to make the extraction,
it needs to be a very...

879
00:49:34,806 --> 00:49:35,932
Sir. Message, sir.

880
00:49:37,308 --> 00:49:39,185
(SIGNAL BEEPING)

881
00:49:39,769 --> 00:49:43,148
GUS: More Jerries
on the island than expected.

882
00:49:45,275 --> 00:49:47,735
Corned beef's out of the pantry
three days early.

883
00:49:48,820 --> 00:49:50,655
Move faster.

884
00:49:50,738 --> 00:49:53,366
M: Yes, but there's increased
U-boat sightings in the area.

885
00:49:53,867 --> 00:49:54,868
Sir.

886
00:49:55,910 --> 00:49:57,912
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

887
00:50:01,791 --> 00:50:03,168
OFFICER: The mission's still proceeding.

888
00:50:06,379 --> 00:50:09,674
FREDDY: So, there's more soldiers on
the island and the boat's leaving earlier?

889
00:50:09,757 --> 00:50:10,758
Yes.

890
00:50:10,842 --> 00:50:13,678
- Well, how are we meant to move faster?
- We can't move faster.

891
00:50:13,761 --> 00:50:15,305
We're going as fast as we can.

892
00:50:15,388 --> 00:50:17,515
This is a fishing boat,
it's not a speedboat.

893
00:50:18,266 --> 00:50:19,267
M: Prime Minister,

894
00:50:19,350 --> 00:50:21,603
the Duchessa's leaving
Fernando Po in 12 days.

895
00:50:21,686 --> 00:50:24,772
On our current schedule,
they'll arrive three days too late.

896
00:50:26,649 --> 00:50:27,650
Can it still be done?

897
00:50:28,359 --> 00:50:31,112
M: We're still awaiting a response
from Major Phillips.

898
00:50:32,822 --> 00:50:34,991
If we can't move faster, we'll go shorter.

899
00:50:35,074 --> 00:50:36,826
We can get to Fernando Po in 12 days.

900
00:50:36,910 --> 00:50:40,038
- Hold on, you said we couldn't go shorter.
- No, I said we don't want to go shorter.

901
00:50:40,121 --> 00:50:42,373
He said we'll get mowed down by a U-boat.

902
00:50:42,957 --> 00:50:45,752
Or worse, picked up by the Brits.

903
00:50:46,252 --> 00:50:47,921
Their armada of destroyers
are crossing there.

904
00:50:48,004 --> 00:50:50,798
FREDDY: We will literally
be sailing over U-boats.

905
00:50:51,633 --> 00:50:54,135
Sorry, lads, we go shorter.

906
00:50:54,219 --> 00:50:56,221
(THRILLING
WESTERN MUSIC PLAYING)

907
00:51:11,444 --> 00:51:13,446
(AIRPLANES ENGINES RUMBLING)

908
00:51:16,950 --> 00:51:20,286
Drei, zwei, eins...
(CONTINUES SPEAKING GERMAN)

909
00:51:25,250 --> 00:51:27,252
(FAINT EXPLOSIONS)

910
00:51:32,674 --> 00:51:34,300
(MUSIC CRESCENDOS, FADES)

911
00:51:36,344 --> 00:51:37,637
(MUTED EXPLOSIONS)

912
00:51:38,763 --> 00:51:41,015
(TENSE WESTERN MUSIC PLAYING)

913
00:51:42,350 --> 00:51:44,519
CHURCHILL: Gentlemen,
as I speak to you now,

914
00:51:45,228 --> 00:51:46,771
London once again

915
00:51:46,854 --> 00:51:49,774
shudders beneath a Nazi
onslaught from the skies.

916
00:51:50,692 --> 00:51:51,776
And at such times,

917
00:51:51,859 --> 00:51:54,445
the hearts of men are stirred to duty.

918
00:51:55,071 --> 00:51:56,489
(OVER RADIO) But you are not such men.

919
00:51:57,031 --> 00:52:00,910
You were not chosen
for your conspicuous honor or high ideals.

920
00:52:01,411 --> 00:52:03,705
You were chosen
because you are the last resort.

921
00:52:04,414 --> 00:52:08,293
The mission you have been given
is of a sort never before undertaken.

922
00:52:09,252 --> 00:52:13,715
It demands ruthless men,
who will not hesitate

923
00:52:13,798 --> 00:52:16,801
to stoop beneath the conventions of war.

924
00:52:17,593 --> 00:52:19,762
Men who do not keep clean hands.

925
00:52:21,597 --> 00:52:22,765
Men like you.

926
00:52:23,349 --> 00:52:24,892
- (FAINT EXPLOSIONS)
- And yet, who still conspire

927
00:52:24,976 --> 00:52:27,603
in their own discordant harmony.

928
00:52:27,687 --> 00:52:31,941
Who know and yet do not care
that they may never return.

929
00:52:32,525 --> 00:52:35,194
And who press onward not for glory,

930
00:52:35,737 --> 00:52:38,156
or for duty, or for me,

931
00:52:38,239 --> 00:52:41,909
but because you are men who will not stop
until it is done.

932
00:52:43,119 --> 00:52:44,537
Godspeed, gentlemen.

933
00:52:45,330 --> 00:52:47,332
(TENSE WESTERN MUSIC CONTINUES)

934
00:52:54,589 --> 00:52:56,549
Uh... Chaps...

935
00:52:58,426 --> 00:53:00,094
That's a British destroyer.

936
00:53:03,556 --> 00:53:04,724
We should move.

937
00:53:05,475 --> 00:53:06,976
We can't outrun that, sir.

938
00:53:09,437 --> 00:53:13,191
Well, we've seen them, they've seen us.

939
00:53:19,280 --> 00:53:20,948
COMMANDER: Hold fast, Maid Honor.

940
00:53:21,032 --> 00:53:22,784
We're preparing a boarding party.

941
00:53:22,867 --> 00:53:24,202
LASSEN: Hello, Captain!

942
00:53:25,370 --> 00:53:26,746
Nothing exciting here.

943
00:53:27,372 --> 00:53:29,290
We're just Swedish fishermen.

944
00:53:29,374 --> 00:53:31,000
COMMANDER: Step forward, Jorgensen!

945
00:53:32,668 --> 00:53:35,505
Jorgensen, you're Swedish.
Ask them where they're heading, would you?

946
00:53:36,422 --> 00:53:37,632
(SPEAKING SWEDISH)

947
00:53:37,715 --> 00:53:40,760
(IN SWEDISH)

948
00:53:40,843 --> 00:53:41,969
(IN ENGLISH) Not you, Lassen.

949
00:53:42,053 --> 00:53:43,054
Uh...

950
00:53:45,431 --> 00:53:47,225
I want to hear March-Phillips have a go.

951
00:53:47,934 --> 00:53:48,935
Ah.

952
00:53:50,853 --> 00:53:51,854
Fair enough.

953
00:53:52,647 --> 00:53:56,401
Game's up, Commander. (CHUCKLES)
Can't blame a girl for trying.

954
00:53:56,484 --> 00:53:59,612
Good effort, Major. But I'm afraid you are
going to have to come with us.

955
00:53:59,695 --> 00:54:02,990
May I ask under whose authority
we've been waylaid?

956
00:54:03,574 --> 00:54:05,076
On the orders of Admiral Pound.

957
00:54:06,369 --> 00:54:07,370
(RADAR PINGS)

958
00:54:10,039 --> 00:54:11,040
OPERATOR: First Lieutenant.

959
00:54:11,124 --> 00:54:14,919
You are pursuing
an unsanctioned criminal enterprise

960
00:54:15,002 --> 00:54:16,879
in international waters.

961
00:54:17,380 --> 00:54:19,132
You're going to cause an upset.

962
00:54:19,215 --> 00:54:22,760
I think we're a little
past upset, Commander.

963
00:54:22,844 --> 00:54:24,387
Stevens, what have you got?

964
00:54:24,470 --> 00:54:25,721
STEVENS: I had a ping, sir.

965
00:54:26,597 --> 00:54:30,435
The greedy little Nazi won't be satisfied
with holding most of Europe,

966
00:54:30,518 --> 00:54:33,104
he's after our own
green and pleasant land.

967
00:54:33,187 --> 00:54:34,439
Well, thank God you're here

968
00:54:34,522 --> 00:54:37,275
with your little wooden battleship
and your five-man army.

969
00:54:38,151 --> 00:54:40,778
- (PINGS)
- U-boat, bearing 273.

970
00:54:40,862 --> 00:54:42,155
- Sound the alarm.
- (ALARM BLARING)

971
00:54:42,238 --> 00:54:43,573
Come aboard.

972
00:54:43,656 --> 00:54:45,533
OFFICER: U-boat approaching.
Starboard side, sir.

973
00:54:45,616 --> 00:54:46,784
Battle stations!

974
00:54:47,618 --> 00:54:49,912
Major, if you know what's good for you,

975
00:54:49,996 --> 00:54:51,831
- you'll head home.
- Very good, Commander.

976
00:54:52,415 --> 00:54:54,876
Haysey, get us away from that
torpedo magnet as quickly as possible.

977
00:54:54,959 --> 00:54:57,420
Aye, sir. Apple, man the stern.

978
00:54:57,503 --> 00:54:58,880
Freddy, on the main sail.

979
00:54:58,963 --> 00:55:01,299
Lassen to the bow, now.
Untie that station!

980
00:55:01,382 --> 00:55:02,592
LASSEN: Aye.

981
00:55:02,675 --> 00:55:03,885
HENRY: Quickly now, lads!

982
00:55:05,052 --> 00:55:07,472
Hoist that foresail for us,
will you, boys?

983
00:55:09,056 --> 00:55:10,558
FREDDY: Main sail ready to haul!

984
00:55:11,601 --> 00:55:13,603
(TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

985
00:55:15,313 --> 00:55:17,231
HENRY: All right, Freddy,
now raise that main sail!

986
00:55:17,315 --> 00:55:18,316
FREDDY: Aye.

987
00:55:18,399 --> 00:55:19,609
- (ALARM CONTINUES)
- OFFICER: Report sounding.

988
00:55:20,193 --> 00:55:21,652
- STEVENS: Bearing 163.
- (PINGS)

989
00:55:25,031 --> 00:55:27,033
(SAILORS SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

990
00:55:30,203 --> 00:55:32,580
HENRY: (IN ENGLISH) Lassen,
trim the main sail and then tie it off!

991
00:55:33,164 --> 00:55:34,582
LASSEN: How do you expect good?

992
00:55:36,292 --> 00:55:37,335
STEVENS: Report sounding.

993
00:55:37,418 --> 00:55:38,920
Bearing 115.

994
00:55:39,003 --> 00:55:40,171
- OFFICER: Fire depth charges.
- (PINGS)

995
00:55:40,254 --> 00:55:42,256
(LEVER CLICKS)

996
00:55:42,340 --> 00:55:44,300
(EXPLOSION BOOMING)

997
00:55:49,305 --> 00:55:51,307
(SAILORS SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

998
00:55:52,558 --> 00:55:55,102
(MUTED EXPLOSIONS)

999
00:55:56,729 --> 00:55:59,273
(ALARM BLARING)

1000
00:56:00,399 --> 00:56:01,400
(MUSIC FADES)

1001
00:56:02,527 --> 00:56:04,529
(DISTANT EXPLOSIONS)

1002
00:56:07,740 --> 00:56:09,992
(PEOPLE SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

1003
00:56:12,453 --> 00:56:13,955
(INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING)

1004
00:56:14,497 --> 00:56:17,250
MARJORIE: So, this is your man
that gets things done?

1005
00:56:17,333 --> 00:56:20,294
His name is Kambili... with a K.

1006
00:56:23,047 --> 00:56:24,882
And he went to an English boarding school?

1007
00:56:26,092 --> 00:56:28,511
Not just any boarding school.

1008
00:56:28,594 --> 00:56:30,888
He went to Eton,

1009
00:56:30,972 --> 00:56:32,348
the boarding school.

1010
00:56:33,766 --> 00:56:34,767
Right...

1011
00:56:35,351 --> 00:56:36,352
(DISTANT GUNSHOT)

1012
00:56:38,521 --> 00:56:39,605
Then what's he doing here?

1013
00:56:40,106 --> 00:56:41,107
He's a prince.

1014
00:56:41,607 --> 00:56:43,067
A prince of what, exactly?

1015
00:56:43,985 --> 00:56:46,821
- The Prince of Fernando Po!
- (GUNSHOT)

1016
00:56:46,904 --> 00:56:50,324
So, he's part pirate, part aristocrat?

1017
00:56:51,325 --> 00:56:52,326
Chic.

1018
00:56:53,077 --> 00:56:55,204
He's also a part of our solution.

1019
00:56:57,498 --> 00:56:58,708
RH.

1020
00:56:58,791 --> 00:56:59,750
(MUSIC FADES)

1021
00:56:59,834 --> 00:57:00,835
KB.

1022
00:57:01,419 --> 00:57:02,587
He's back in town.

1023
00:57:02,670 --> 00:57:03,671
MAN: Chief.

1024
00:57:04,839 --> 00:57:06,882
(MAN SPEAKING YORUBA)

1025
00:57:08,593 --> 00:57:09,635
(GUNSHOT)

1026
00:57:11,512 --> 00:57:14,181
(IN ENGLISH) Seems like
you always come bearing gifts.

1027
00:57:15,975 --> 00:57:16,976
Is she for me?

1028
00:57:17,685 --> 00:57:19,395
- Good luck with that.
- (CHUCKLES)

1029
00:57:20,313 --> 00:57:21,314
I'm not for you,

1030
00:57:22,356 --> 00:57:23,357
but these are.

1031
00:57:23,858 --> 00:57:26,235
Mmm. Goodies. Yummy.

1032
00:57:26,319 --> 00:57:28,279
- (MEN GRUNT)
- (MAN SPEAKING YORUBA)

1033
00:57:29,071 --> 00:57:30,406
- (IN ENGLISH) Ade...
- Chief.

1034
00:57:31,240 --> 00:57:32,533
ADEDAYO: Come on, come on.

1035
00:57:32,617 --> 00:57:33,743
(MEN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

1036
00:57:36,245 --> 00:57:37,747
Someone has taste.

1037
00:57:38,748 --> 00:57:40,499
Rarer than hens' teeth.

1038
00:57:40,583 --> 00:57:45,171
Well, RH tells me that KB

1039
00:57:45,254 --> 00:57:48,215
is the only man to talk to
when it comes to getting things done.

1040
00:57:49,175 --> 00:57:50,885
Why do I feel like I've gone from being

1041
00:57:50,968 --> 00:57:53,554
- the predator to the prey?
- (COCKS GUN)

1042
00:57:57,016 --> 00:57:58,059
(GUNSHOT)

1043
00:57:58,684 --> 00:58:00,019
(CLEARS THROAT)

1044
00:58:00,645 --> 00:58:02,063
Quite an entrance, young lady.

1045
00:58:02,772 --> 00:58:04,565
It's on the condition
that we sample them...

1046
00:58:05,733 --> 00:58:06,734
NOW.

1047
00:58:10,112 --> 00:58:11,447
Ade, set the table.

1048
00:58:11,530 --> 00:58:12,573
ADEDAYO: Chief.

1049
00:58:12,657 --> 00:58:16,577
(LAUGHING) And then the Duke said,
"Push it in till it stops!"

1050
00:58:16,661 --> 00:58:18,704
(ALL LAUGHING)

1051
00:58:22,375 --> 00:58:25,044
You are quite the weapon.

1052
00:58:25,670 --> 00:58:26,754
I was right,

1053
00:58:27,630 --> 00:58:28,923
I was the prey.

1054
00:58:31,967 --> 00:58:35,262
I'll help you because I don't like Nazis.

1055
00:58:35,346 --> 00:58:38,015
Not because they're Nazis
but because they're gauche.

1056
00:58:38,599 --> 00:58:42,144
I'll give you a tug and 12 of my best men,
including yours truly.

1057
00:58:43,646 --> 00:58:45,940
But if I'm gonna help you,
who's gonna help me?

1058
00:58:46,649 --> 00:58:48,693
Because you're not a soldier, RH.

1059
00:58:49,777 --> 00:58:52,113
No, but she is.

1060
00:58:55,282 --> 00:58:56,909
She'll out shoot your best man.

1061
00:58:58,953 --> 00:58:59,954
(BLOWS RASPBERRY)

1062
00:59:04,959 --> 00:59:06,252
(GUNSHOT)

1063
00:59:10,923 --> 00:59:12,091
(COCKS GUN)

1064
00:59:13,050 --> 00:59:14,176
(GUNSHOT)

1065
00:59:19,265 --> 00:59:20,349
(COCKS GUN)

1066
00:59:20,433 --> 00:59:21,851
(GUNSHOTS)

1067
00:59:30,693 --> 00:59:31,736
(BLOWS)

1068
00:59:33,863 --> 00:59:34,864
I told you.

1069
00:59:38,576 --> 00:59:39,410
- No!
- No!

1070
00:59:39,493 --> 00:59:42,079
(MYSTERIOUS MUSIC PLAYING)

1071
00:59:42,163 --> 00:59:43,873
MARJORIE: Stork delivery. Check.

1072
00:59:44,957 --> 00:59:45,958
Check.

1073
00:59:46,041 --> 00:59:47,877
Twenty-three boys. Check.

1074
00:59:48,961 --> 00:59:50,629
- (SIGNAL BEEPING)
- Stork delivery.

1075
00:59:53,132 --> 00:59:56,135
Twenty-three boys.

1076
00:59:56,218 --> 00:59:58,721
Seventeen girls.

1077
00:59:59,305 --> 01:00:02,808
Meeting point 20 kilometers
outside Fernando Po.

1078
01:00:04,101 --> 01:00:05,102
The rendezvous with Heron.

1079
01:00:06,479 --> 01:00:07,521
Can you get us there?

1080
01:00:07,605 --> 01:00:11,192
If the weather holds, I can, sir.

1081
01:00:11,275 --> 01:00:13,235
(MYSTERIOUS MUSIC CONTINUES)

1082
01:00:28,375 --> 01:00:30,169
Twenty quid says this doesn't end well.

1083
01:00:31,045 --> 01:00:32,046
For who?

1084
01:00:32,546 --> 01:00:33,547
For them.

1085
01:00:33,631 --> 01:00:36,425
You can't bet on yourself,
Haysey. That's match-fixing.

1086
01:00:38,469 --> 01:00:39,470
Let's do it.

1087
01:00:40,638 --> 01:00:42,139
Heron, it's been too long.

1088
01:00:42,223 --> 01:00:43,808
Good to see you, Gus.

1089
01:00:43,891 --> 01:00:45,059
Apple.

1090
01:00:46,685 --> 01:00:49,647
This is Kambili,
the Prince of Fernando Po.

1091
01:00:50,439 --> 01:00:51,607
Your Highness.

1092
01:00:51,690 --> 01:00:52,983
He's agreed to help us.

1093
01:00:54,276 --> 01:00:55,611
Forgive me, but...

1094
01:00:56,612 --> 01:00:59,615
I have a peculiar feeling
that we've met before.

1095
01:01:00,574 --> 01:01:04,078
I get that a lot.
I'm extremely well-traveled.

1096
01:01:04,161 --> 01:01:06,789
(CHUCKLES) No, no.
It's a particular sense.

1097
01:01:09,291 --> 01:01:12,962
I don't suppose
you played cricket, did you?

1098
01:01:13,045 --> 01:01:14,046
(CHUCKLES)

1099
01:01:15,130 --> 01:01:17,675
Captained Eton. '21 to "22.

1100
01:01:17,758 --> 01:01:20,094
I knew I knew your face!

1101
01:01:20,177 --> 01:01:22,096
Right next to the trophy cabinet.

1102
01:01:22,179 --> 01:01:24,431
An eight-foot-tall huge portrait.

1103
01:01:24,974 --> 01:01:27,184
Yes, exactly that!

1104
01:01:27,768 --> 01:01:28,978
One eye on the boundary...

1105
01:01:29,061 --> 01:01:30,646
BOTH: ...one eye on the pub.

1106
01:01:30,729 --> 01:01:32,314
Bloody glad to have you aboard.

1107
01:01:32,398 --> 01:01:33,941
KAMBILl: Bloody good to be here, old boy.

1108
01:01:34,525 --> 01:01:38,320
I'm very bored with these Nazis making
a nuisance of themselves.

1109
01:01:38,404 --> 01:01:39,989
I mean, it's terrible for business.

1110
01:01:40,072 --> 01:01:44,785
I'm only too pleased
to help you serve them a bloody nose.

1111
01:01:44,869 --> 01:01:46,579
That's a commendable attitude.

1112
01:01:46,662 --> 01:01:48,664
So, what's your plan?

1113
01:01:48,747 --> 01:01:49,748
Apple.

1114
01:01:50,958 --> 01:01:53,127
We're going to sink the Duchessa,
plus the two tugs.

1115
01:01:53,711 --> 01:01:55,963
Crippling Hitler's
Atlantic fleet of U-boats.

1116
01:01:56,046 --> 01:01:57,256
Very good.

1117
01:01:57,339 --> 01:02:01,385
The thing is, our old friends the Nazis
aren't making it the easiest.

1118
01:02:01,468 --> 01:02:03,345
We're outnumbered two hundred to five.

1119
01:02:03,429 --> 01:02:05,472
There's a few more soldiers
than we anticipated.

1120
01:02:06,515 --> 01:02:09,852
I think that we're gonna have to find
ourselves a few more strapping lads.

1121
01:02:10,728 --> 01:02:11,770
Ade...

1122
01:02:11,854 --> 01:02:12,855
(SPEAKING YORUBA)

1123
01:02:16,066 --> 01:02:18,444
(INTRIGUING
WESTERN MUSIC PLAYING)

1124
01:02:21,780 --> 01:02:23,282
(IN ENGLISH) Right...

1125
01:02:26,201 --> 01:02:27,286
(CHOMPING)

1126
01:02:27,369 --> 01:02:28,579
Yes, I think that will do.

1127
01:02:29,914 --> 01:02:32,416
We brought some weapons if you need.

1128
01:02:32,499 --> 01:02:34,585
You hold onto those. We brought our own.

1129
01:02:34,668 --> 01:02:36,086
(SPEAKING YORUBA)

1130
01:02:37,254 --> 01:02:39,757
(IN ENGLISH) Oyah! Show them the iron!

1131
01:02:39,840 --> 01:02:41,383
(ADEDAYO SPEAKING YORUBA)

1132
01:02:42,760 --> 01:02:43,802
(IN ENGLISH) Marvelous.

1133
01:02:44,386 --> 01:02:48,390
KAMBILl: You do know the Duchessa is
more than 200 feet from the harbor side?

1134
01:02:48,474 --> 01:02:51,143
And she's in full glare of the lights.

1135
01:02:51,226 --> 01:02:54,897
She's not gonna be easy to sink
without attracting unwanted attention.

1136
01:02:54,980 --> 01:02:58,400
Yes. That's why Heron will plant a bomb

1137
01:02:58,484 --> 01:03:00,653
to blow the lights, before we paddle in

1138
01:03:00,736 --> 01:03:03,113
and rig the hull with explosives.

1139
01:03:03,656 --> 01:03:07,117
By the time the explosives detonate,
we'll be heading home.

1140
01:03:07,201 --> 01:03:09,286
If I had it my way,
a shot'll never be fired.

1141
01:03:09,370 --> 01:03:11,497
And how often do you have it your way?

1142
01:03:12,206 --> 01:03:13,958
Depends on who you ask, old boy.

1143
01:03:14,041 --> 01:03:15,250
(KAMBILl CHUCKLES)

1144
01:03:16,293 --> 01:03:17,336
GUS: Gentlemen...

1145
01:03:17,419 --> 01:03:18,712
- Ade.
- Chief.

1146
01:03:18,796 --> 01:03:20,798
- Prepare the men.
- (ADEDAYO SPEAKING YORUBA)

1147
01:03:20,881 --> 01:03:23,008
I'll take that 20
whenever you're ready, Freddy.

1148
01:03:25,636 --> 01:03:27,596
(INDISTINCT ANNOUNCEMENT
OVER SPEAKERS)

1149
01:03:41,568 --> 01:03:43,404
MARJORIE: The Duchessa
will be gone by the morning.

1150
01:03:44,571 --> 01:03:45,990
- Can you manage that?
- (BOMB CLICKING)

1151
01:03:47,908 --> 01:03:50,327
It's two wires and a ticktock.

1152
01:03:51,620 --> 01:03:53,122
I'm sure I can cope.

1153
01:03:54,748 --> 01:03:56,834
It's not me you should be worried about.

1154
01:03:59,336 --> 01:04:01,422
I've never taken a Nazi to a party.

1155
01:04:04,299 --> 01:04:07,177
Just don't end up at one of his parties.

1156
01:04:11,306 --> 01:04:12,474
Don't worry about me.

1157
01:04:13,600 --> 01:04:15,644
I'm gonna have my own little party.

1158
01:04:16,895 --> 01:04:18,856
(MEN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

1159
01:04:18,939 --> 01:04:19,940
(MUSIC FADES)

1160
01:04:20,733 --> 01:04:22,818
GUS: Drink for the boys,
on His Majesty's government.

1161
01:04:27,573 --> 01:04:29,575
Ordinarily, I'd bite your hand off,

1162
01:04:30,576 --> 01:04:32,745
as I have been known to love a pound note.

1163
01:04:32,828 --> 01:04:35,789
(SPEAKING YORUBA)

1164
01:04:36,707 --> 01:04:41,545
(IN ENGLISH) But on this occasion,
the drinks are on me.

1165
01:04:42,713 --> 01:04:43,756
However,

1166
01:04:43,839 --> 01:04:46,592
if His Majesty's government
was handing out titles...

1167
01:04:47,551 --> 01:04:49,553
You're already a prince, old boy.

1168
01:04:49,636 --> 01:04:52,264
There's Prince of Fernando Po, but...

1169
01:04:52,890 --> 01:04:55,893
a Knight of the Realm
has a certain antiquity to it.

1170
01:04:58,437 --> 01:05:00,814
Arise, Sir Kambili.

1171
01:05:03,025 --> 01:05:04,526
You're a good man, Gus.

1172
01:05:05,486 --> 01:05:06,487
Good luck, Billy.

1173
01:05:08,864 --> 01:05:10,491
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

1174
01:05:10,574 --> 01:05:12,534
(MACHINERY WHIRRING)

1175
01:05:17,122 --> 01:05:18,290
Hola!

1176
01:05:19,708 --> 01:05:21,710
Buenas tardes, compañeros!

1177
01:05:36,767 --> 01:05:37,768
(CLICKS)

1178
01:05:53,700 --> 01:05:54,785
(SOLDIER, IN GERMAN)

1179
01:05:58,497 --> 01:06:00,499
(MUSIC TURNS DRAMATIC)

1180
01:06:20,853 --> 01:06:23,063
(IN GERMAN) What are you doing here?

1181
01:06:23,147 --> 01:06:25,023
(GUNSHOTS)

1182
01:06:26,984 --> 01:06:28,735
(GUN CLICKS)

1183
01:06:43,792 --> 01:06:45,711
(SCREAMING)

1184
01:06:47,462 --> 01:06:50,215
- (BODY SLIDES, THUDS)
- (MUSIC FADES)

1185
01:06:50,299 --> 01:06:52,301
(BOMB TICKING)

1186
01:06:56,388 --> 01:06:58,348
(GENTLE PIANO MUSIC PLAYING)

1187
01:06:58,974 --> 01:07:00,726
My Herr, you have a visitor.

1188
01:07:04,104 --> 01:07:05,397
Ta-da!

1189
01:07:10,194 --> 01:07:12,529
(IN SING-SONG VOICE)
Cleopatra needs her Caesar.

1190
01:07:13,197 --> 01:07:14,198
Put it on.

1191
01:07:16,617 --> 01:07:17,743
(SNORTS)

1192
01:07:17,826 --> 01:07:18,994
Thank you, Timothy.

1193
01:07:19,786 --> 01:07:20,871
One second.

1194
01:07:21,455 --> 01:07:22,456
Timothy...

1195
01:07:24,333 --> 01:07:26,043
I have a counter offer.

1196
01:07:26,126 --> 01:07:28,337
Let's put this dressing up aside.

1197
01:07:28,420 --> 01:07:31,256
It's for children.
And we are not children.

1198
01:07:34,343 --> 01:07:35,928
Let's make our own party.

1199
01:07:36,929 --> 01:07:38,263
A dark party.

1200
01:07:39,264 --> 01:07:41,433
A dark Nazi party.

1201
01:07:42,351 --> 01:07:46,897
With music, lubrication
and a handsome Nazi.

1202
01:07:48,106 --> 01:07:49,191
Since I've been here,

1203
01:07:49,274 --> 01:07:52,527
I've been bitten by things
that croak and slither,

1204
01:07:52,611 --> 01:07:54,780
scorpions nest in my boots
and I can't sleep

1205
01:07:54,863 --> 01:07:57,032
for the relentless howl of jungle entropy.

1206
01:07:57,616 --> 01:07:58,659
Tonight,

1207
01:07:58,742 --> 01:08:03,038
I'm going to that party,
and you are taking me.

1208
01:08:04,706 --> 01:08:06,875
Now, put it on.

1209
01:08:08,043 --> 01:08:09,044
(CLICKS TONGUE) Oh.

1210
01:08:10,128 --> 01:08:11,129
Very well.

1211
01:08:11,672 --> 01:08:13,590
(EXCITING MUSIC PLAYING)

1212
01:08:16,510 --> 01:08:18,470
(PEOPLE SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

1213
01:08:25,602 --> 01:08:27,604
(LAUGHTER)

1214
01:08:51,753 --> 01:08:53,255
WOMAN: Ah! Hola!

1215
01:09:07,519 --> 01:09:08,937
We move when the lights go out.

1216
01:09:09,688 --> 01:09:11,648
- ( WOMAN WHOOPING)
- (BAND PLAYING SWING MUSIC)

1217
01:09:20,449 --> 01:09:21,450
(MAN LAUGHING)

1218
01:09:27,247 --> 01:09:28,832
All right, Ricardo,

1219
01:09:30,083 --> 01:09:32,794
today you're El Capitán.

1220
01:09:32,878 --> 01:09:35,756
Armando, the bar is yours.

1221
01:09:36,298 --> 01:09:38,425
Use it. Abuse it at your will.

1222
01:09:38,508 --> 01:09:40,761
BINEA: (CHUCKLES) That's why I love you.

1223
01:09:41,345 --> 01:09:42,554
Come with me, handsome.

1224
01:09:43,180 --> 01:09:45,557
(BINEA SPEAKING SPANISH)

1225
01:09:47,017 --> 01:09:48,935
HERON: I need you to keep the men happy.

1226
01:09:51,355 --> 01:09:52,356
How happy?

1227
01:09:59,363 --> 01:10:00,906
(BAND CONTINUES PLAYING
SWING MUSIC)

1228
01:10:08,747 --> 01:10:10,082
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATION)

1229
01:10:10,916 --> 01:10:11,917
MARJORIE: Mmm.

1230
01:10:14,544 --> 01:10:16,171
Are the rats in the nest?

1231
01:10:17,005 --> 01:10:20,634
You won't find a German,
Spanish or Italian officer

1232
01:10:20,717 --> 01:10:22,010
anywhere else tonight.

1233
01:10:22,094 --> 01:10:24,346
- (SWING MUSIC CONTINUES)
- (PEOPLE CHEERING)

1234
01:10:27,891 --> 01:10:30,685
HERON: Between the beer fest at the harbor
and this little get-together,

1235
01:10:31,186 --> 01:10:33,605
that'll be 90% of the soldiers
away from the dock.

1236
01:10:35,065 --> 01:10:38,110
The charge is set to blow
the harbor lights in 30 minutes.

1237
01:10:39,736 --> 01:10:41,363
Can you keep him here that long?

1238
01:10:41,905 --> 01:10:44,825
Silly boy, silly question.
Look at the dress.

1239
01:10:49,704 --> 01:10:50,664
(MAN CHEERS)

1240
01:10:51,540 --> 01:10:52,791
(LAUGHS)

1241
01:10:52,874 --> 01:10:54,376
(TRUMPET FLARES)

1242
01:10:55,210 --> 01:10:56,253
Hi.

1243
01:10:56,336 --> 01:10:58,422
So, you call this a party?

1244
01:10:58,505 --> 01:11:00,132
MARJORIE: This is just
the thin end of the wedge.

1245
01:11:00,215 --> 01:11:02,300
I've created a performance just for you.

1246
01:11:02,926 --> 01:11:05,720
Well, I could show you a real party.

1247
01:11:05,804 --> 01:11:06,930
(MARJORIE CHUCKLES)

1248
01:11:07,013 --> 01:11:08,140
(IN ITALIAN)

1249
01:11:08,223 --> 01:11:09,599
(PEOPLE CHEERING, APPLAUDING)

1250
01:11:13,437 --> 01:11:15,063
- (LAUGHS)
- (FRANTIC MUSIC PLAYING)

1251
01:11:17,315 --> 01:11:18,316
(IN ITALIAN)

1252
01:11:32,873 --> 01:11:34,458
(IN ENGLISH) Why do I care, Spaghetti?

1253
01:11:34,541 --> 01:11:35,667
Pizza.

1254
01:11:36,543 --> 01:11:38,503
Excuse me while I powder my nose.

1255
01:11:38,587 --> 01:11:40,464
- What, again?
- (SCOFFS)

1256
01:11:40,547 --> 01:11:42,549
Don't panic, Caesar.
Brush up on your Italian.

1257
01:11:43,091 --> 01:11:44,843
Your gift needs to be wrapped.

1258
01:11:45,594 --> 01:11:47,471
Keep those officers drinking, please.

1259
01:11:47,554 --> 01:11:49,097
- Of course. Okay.
- Thank you, Femi.

1260
01:11:49,598 --> 01:11:51,558
The Duchessa's hull has been reinforced.

1261
01:11:52,434 --> 01:11:53,435
It won't sink.

1262
01:11:54,644 --> 01:11:55,937
We need to stop the mission.

1263
01:11:56,021 --> 01:11:57,606
(FRANTIC MUSIC CONTINUES)

1264
01:12:02,527 --> 01:12:03,904
That's going to be hard to do.

1265
01:12:03,987 --> 01:12:05,030
MARJORIE: Listen to me.

1266
01:12:05,530 --> 01:12:06,531
Our mission will fail.

1267
01:12:07,032 --> 01:12:10,911
The explosives won't work because he's
reinforced it to be unsinkable.

1268
01:12:12,412 --> 01:12:13,622
You have to stop them now.

1269
01:12:16,500 --> 01:12:19,377
But the charge is about
to blow the lights.

1270
01:12:19,461 --> 01:12:20,921
(BOMB TICKING)

1271
01:12:21,505 --> 01:12:23,757
Well, if you can't stop the lights,
stop the men.

1272
01:12:23,840 --> 01:12:25,634
Luhr must not leave this party.

1273
01:12:26,510 --> 01:12:28,553
I'll keep him busy. Go, now.

1274
01:12:32,307 --> 01:12:33,975
(MUSIC INTENSIFIES)

1275
01:12:53,703 --> 01:12:54,704
(MUSIC FADES)

1276
01:13:00,377 --> 01:13:02,629
(BAND PLAYING SWING MUSIC)

1277
01:13:08,051 --> 01:13:09,261
GUS:And we're off.

1278
01:13:09,761 --> 01:13:10,971
GEOFFREY: Gus, wait.

1279
01:13:11,054 --> 01:13:12,931
(TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

1280
01:13:24,401 --> 01:13:26,027
(SIGNAL BEEPING)

1281
01:13:30,615 --> 01:13:33,243
Stork to Maid, Stork to Maid, come in.

1282
01:13:34,452 --> 01:13:35,453
Channel five.

1283
01:13:35,537 --> 01:13:36,997
GUS: (OVER RADIO)
This is Maid. Switching to 20.

1284
01:13:40,083 --> 01:13:41,084
Go ahead.

1285
01:13:41,626 --> 01:13:43,837
Tin of corned beef can't be cracked.

1286
01:13:44,588 --> 01:13:46,298
The ship cannot be sunk.

1287
01:13:47,090 --> 01:13:48,800
Explosives will fail.

1288
01:13:49,884 --> 01:13:50,885
It's Stork, sir.

1289
01:13:51,386 --> 01:13:52,512
Put him on open speaker.

1290
01:13:53,680 --> 01:13:55,599
HERON: Corned beef can't be cracked.

1291
01:13:56,141 --> 01:13:57,350
Stork, this is M.

1292
01:13:57,434 --> 01:13:59,477
Never mind the corned beef.
Just find a way.

1293
01:13:59,561 --> 01:14:00,687
- Over.
- Pound incoming, sir.

1294
01:14:01,605 --> 01:14:03,023
- HERON: Repeat...
- Switch that off.

1295
01:14:03,106 --> 01:14:04,190
- We must...
- (TURNS OFF RADIO)

1296
01:14:04,691 --> 01:14:05,734
(DOOR OPENS)

1297
01:14:05,817 --> 01:14:07,444
Stop this immediately.

1298
01:14:08,028 --> 01:14:10,780
What you are doing ends now,

1299
01:14:10,864 --> 01:14:13,199
or every last one of you
will be subject to a tribunal.

1300
01:14:13,283 --> 01:14:14,284
Is that clear?

1301
01:14:14,951 --> 01:14:17,287
I don't know what
you're talking about, sir.

1302
01:14:18,455 --> 01:14:21,124
Is that correct, Sergeant?

1303
01:14:24,711 --> 01:14:26,129
HERON: (OVER RADIO) Hold position.

1304
01:14:26,212 --> 01:14:28,214
GUS: How long, Stork?

1305
01:14:28,298 --> 01:14:29,466
- HERON: Awaiting orders.
- Give me that.

1306
01:14:29,549 --> 01:14:30,550
HERON: Stand by.

1307
01:14:31,426 --> 01:14:32,427
March-Phillips,

1308
01:14:32,510 --> 01:14:35,221
this is Admiral Pound
giving you a direct order.

1309
01:14:35,722 --> 01:14:37,349
Abort this mission now.

1310
01:14:37,432 --> 01:14:40,435
(OVER SPEAKERS) I will make sure that
none of you see the light of day again.

1311
01:14:40,518 --> 01:14:43,730
You will spend the rest of your lives
locked up at His Majesty's pleasure.

1312
01:14:43,813 --> 01:14:44,856
That includes all of you.

1313
01:14:44,939 --> 01:14:46,566
Geoffrey Apple yard,

1314
01:14:46,650 --> 01:14:47,692
Anders Lassen,

1315
01:14:47,776 --> 01:14:48,860
- Freddy Buzz...
- GUS: I'm sorry...

1316
01:14:48,943 --> 01:14:50,028
...and Henry Hayes.

1317
01:14:50,111 --> 01:14:51,154
Can't quite make out

1318
01:14:51,237 --> 01:14:52,614
- what you're saying.
- (RADIO STATIC CRACKLING)

1319
01:14:54,032 --> 01:14:55,033
Bye.

1320
01:14:55,575 --> 01:14:56,910
- Is... Is that clear?
- (RADIO STATIC CRACKLES)

1321
01:14:56,993 --> 01:14:58,411
GUS: Sorry? What?

1322
01:14:58,495 --> 01:15:00,330
I can't... I can't quite hear you.

1323
01:15:00,413 --> 01:15:01,456
(HESITATES)

1324
01:15:01,539 --> 01:15:03,208
GUS: Please... fuck off.

1325
01:15:05,043 --> 01:15:06,044
(RECEIVER CLATTERS)

1326
01:15:08,254 --> 01:15:10,757
You and your operation
are reckless, Brigadier.

1327
01:15:11,841 --> 01:15:13,593
I will personally advise parliament

1328
01:15:13,677 --> 01:15:16,221
to have the Prime Minister
removed from office.

1329
01:15:16,846 --> 01:15:18,723
And I am going to shut you down.

1330
01:15:20,100 --> 01:15:22,936
Message received loud and clear, sir.

1331
01:15:29,484 --> 01:15:31,695
I suggest you also fuck off, Sergeant.

1332
01:15:32,362 --> 01:15:34,155
Fleming, contact March-Phillips.

1333
01:15:37,200 --> 01:15:38,243
- (RADIO CLICKS)
- (STATIC CRACKLES)

1334
01:15:38,326 --> 01:15:39,911
Lily, get me
the Prime Minister on hotline.

1335
01:15:39,994 --> 01:15:41,329
- LILY: Right away, sir.
- Come in, 01.

1336
01:15:41,413 --> 01:15:42,664
Come in, do you receive?

1337
01:15:42,747 --> 01:15:43,748
(RECEIVER CLATTERS)

1338
01:15:44,290 --> 01:15:46,251
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

1339
01:15:47,711 --> 01:15:49,337
- Yes?
- M: Prime Minister,

1340
01:15:49,421 --> 01:15:51,172
I'm afraid we've been discovered.

1341
01:15:52,048 --> 01:15:53,133
(SIGHS)

1342
01:15:53,883 --> 01:15:55,301
There was a mole in our midst

1343
01:15:55,385 --> 01:15:58,221
and Admiral Pound
has ordered the mission to be aborted.

1344
01:15:58,304 --> 01:16:01,057
He wants to have parliament
remove you from office.

1345
01:16:02,225 --> 01:16:03,435
The mission must continue.

1346
01:16:03,518 --> 01:16:04,978
01, this is base. Over.

1347
01:16:05,103 --> 01:16:07,564
CHURCHILL: Tell Pound if he has a problem,
to take it up with me.

1348
01:16:07,647 --> 01:16:10,358
He knows where I live.
Tell the men to press on.

1349
01:16:10,442 --> 01:16:12,819
I'm afraid we've lost
all communication, sir.

1350
01:16:16,322 --> 01:16:17,741
There must be something that we can do.

1351
01:16:17,824 --> 01:16:20,660
The only thing I can do is remind you,

1352
01:16:20,744 --> 01:16:22,787
the reason we chose March-Phillips

1353
01:16:22,871 --> 01:16:25,498
is because he doesn't follow orders.

1354
01:16:28,334 --> 01:16:29,919
Then let's hope we chose well.

1355
01:16:30,837 --> 01:16:31,838
(RECEIVER CLATTERS)

1356
01:16:31,921 --> 01:16:33,047
(SIGHS)

1357
01:16:35,175 --> 01:16:37,510
The Duchessa's hull has been reinforced.

1358
01:16:37,594 --> 01:16:39,471
Which means she can't be sunk.

1359
01:16:39,554 --> 01:16:42,807
At least not with the amount
of explosives we're carrying.

1360
01:16:42,891 --> 01:16:45,018
Just wondering how and when
exactly this took place.

1361
01:16:45,101 --> 01:16:46,936
It's not important
how and when, it's happened.

1362
01:16:47,020 --> 01:16:49,147
Well, it is kind of important, Gus.

1363
01:16:49,230 --> 01:16:51,065
I don't care about the prison time,

1364
01:16:51,149 --> 01:16:53,151
but I do care about finishing
what we've started.

1365
01:16:53,234 --> 01:16:54,444
Thank you, Freddy.

1366
01:16:54,527 --> 01:16:56,654
There must be some sort of mistake.
You can't just reinforce...

1367
01:16:56,738 --> 01:16:58,531
There's no mistake, Haysey.

1368
01:16:58,615 --> 01:17:00,325
I'm just lost about
how and when exactly...

1369
01:17:00,408 --> 01:17:01,743
- Enough!
- (TABLE RATTLES)

1370
01:17:10,251 --> 01:17:14,714
Why don't we sink the tug boats?
Get rid of the shuttle to the U-boats.

1371
01:17:15,965 --> 01:17:18,802
It's not enough.
They'll replace them in a week.

1372
01:17:28,978 --> 01:17:30,063
Why don't we steal them?

1373
01:17:30,146 --> 01:17:33,024
We can use Billy's boat
to drag the Duchessa out of the harbor

1374
01:17:33,107 --> 01:17:35,985
and steal the other two German tug boats
that service the U-boats.

1375
01:17:36,069 --> 01:17:37,862
And how are we supposed to do that?

1376
01:17:37,946 --> 01:17:41,574
Not only is she double-plated,
weighing twice as much,

1377
01:17:41,658 --> 01:17:43,409
but you'd need a full crew
to move a ship that size.

1378
01:17:43,493 --> 01:17:45,036
The tug boats are the crew.

1379
01:17:45,119 --> 01:17:49,666
We tow the Duchessa out to the ocean
and, well, steal the lot.

1380
01:17:50,291 --> 01:17:52,919
Then what? We still can't sink them.

1381
01:17:54,045 --> 01:17:55,296
We don't need to.

1382
01:17:55,380 --> 01:17:58,424
We sail into international waters
and hand everything over to the Navy.

1383
01:17:58,508 --> 01:17:59,717
They're following us anyway,

1384
01:17:59,801 --> 01:18:01,094
so they'll be more than happy
to see us again.

1385
01:18:01,177 --> 01:18:04,973
And what about the anchor?
Have you seen the size of it?

1386
01:18:05,056 --> 01:18:09,143
If we're gonna actually start to move her,
their S-boats will catch us in seconds.

1387
01:18:09,227 --> 01:18:11,688
Well, what are you going to do with
all the explosives you brought, Freddy?

1388
01:18:13,481 --> 01:18:15,400
We'll use them to blow the anchor.

1389
01:18:15,483 --> 01:18:17,694
We'll rig the S-boats
so they can't follow,

1390
01:18:17,777 --> 01:18:20,029
rig the fuel reserve
that supplies the U-boats,

1391
01:18:20,113 --> 01:18:23,616
and then, well, blow the lot up.

1392
01:18:23,700 --> 01:18:25,159
That fuel explosion's gonna bring

1393
01:18:25,243 --> 01:18:26,828
everyone and their mother
down to the harbor.

1394
01:18:26,911 --> 01:18:27,954
GEOFFREY: We set the fuse,

1395
01:18:28,037 --> 01:18:30,623
so that the fuel dump blows
once we're outside the harbor.

1396
01:18:31,249 --> 01:18:33,751
Then we sneak out quietly.

1397
01:18:35,295 --> 01:18:36,296
Not bad.

1398
01:18:37,839 --> 01:18:39,674
(CHUCKLES) It's very greedy.

1399
01:18:41,384 --> 01:18:42,927
- Well, I'm in.
- LASSEN: Well,

1400
01:18:43,928 --> 01:18:46,806
I'm not leaving until I have
a barrel full of Nazi hearts.

1401
01:18:46,890 --> 01:18:49,559
I'll do whatever you tell me to do, sir.

1402
01:18:52,186 --> 01:18:53,187
Gentlemen,

1403
01:18:57,984 --> 01:19:00,320
let's steal some boats.

1404
01:19:06,367 --> 01:19:07,535
(GUS SIGHS)

1405
01:19:08,995 --> 01:19:12,290
Turns out she's double-plated,
so change of plans.

1406
01:19:14,000 --> 01:19:15,877
We're going to steal the boats instead.

1407
01:19:15,960 --> 01:19:16,961
(SCOFFS)

1408
01:19:18,880 --> 01:19:20,256
Is that even possible?

1409
01:19:21,966 --> 01:19:23,343
I'm not entirely sure.

1410
01:19:26,137 --> 01:19:27,764
But if you're up for it, SO are we.

1411
01:19:28,806 --> 01:19:30,058
And you know what that means.

1412
01:19:31,267 --> 01:19:33,353
A lot more blood and a lot more sweat.

1413
01:19:33,937 --> 01:19:35,813
Hopefully not any of ours, old boy.

1414
01:19:37,815 --> 01:19:39,943
I don't think we can do this
without you, Billy.

1415
01:19:41,069 --> 01:19:42,487
(KAMBILl SIGHS)

1416
01:19:49,077 --> 01:19:51,829
Well, I'm up for it if you are.

1417
01:19:53,831 --> 01:19:55,291
I think we're gonna need your tug.

1418
01:19:55,375 --> 01:19:56,376
(KAMBILl CHUCKLES)

1419
01:19:58,252 --> 01:20:00,380
Haysey and I will
take a stroll along the harbor

1420
01:20:00,463 --> 01:20:02,590
and take out
any soldiers still patrolling.

1421
01:20:03,383 --> 01:20:06,094
Freddy will bring his dinghy around
and take care of the S-boats.

1422
01:20:06,177 --> 01:20:07,595
We'll meet you by the tug boats.

1423
01:20:08,888 --> 01:20:09,889
KAMBILl: And the Duchessa?

1424
01:20:10,390 --> 01:20:11,766
That's Apple and me.

1425
01:20:11,849 --> 01:20:14,185
We'll take care of any crew
and blow the anchor.

1426
01:20:14,268 --> 01:20:15,770
GEOFFREY: And destroy their comms.

1427
01:20:17,522 --> 01:20:19,524
Not sure what you'll meet on board.

1428
01:20:19,607 --> 01:20:22,151
Take my top boy and two more of my men.

1429
01:20:22,235 --> 01:20:23,945
(TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

1430
01:20:24,028 --> 01:20:26,072
Gentlemen, let's prepare.

1431
01:20:34,288 --> 01:20:37,250
(SINGING) Oh, the shark, babe

1432
01:20:37,333 --> 01:20:40,420
Has such teeth, dear

1433
01:20:40,503 --> 01:20:45,341
And he shows them pearly white

1434
01:20:45,425 --> 01:20:46,467
(CROWD CHEERING)

1435
01:20:46,551 --> 01:20:49,220
Just a jack-knife

1436
01:20:49,303 --> 01:20:52,098
Has old MacHeath, dear

1437
01:20:53,016 --> 01:20:57,937
And he keeps it out of sight

1438
01:20:58,479 --> 01:21:01,524
You know when that shark bites

1439
01:21:01,607 --> 01:21:04,444
With his teeth, dear

1440
01:21:05,862 --> 01:21:11,117
Scarlet billows starts to spread

1441
01:21:11,868 --> 01:21:16,706
Fancy gloves, oh,
wears old MacHeath, dear

1442
01:21:17,290 --> 01:21:22,003
So there's never, never a trace of red

1443
01:21:23,129 --> 01:21:26,257
On the sidewalk

1444
01:21:26,340 --> 01:21:29,302
On Sunday morning, don't you know

1445
01:21:29,385 --> 01:21:31,429
Lies a body

1446
01:21:32,263 --> 01:21:35,183
Oozing life

1447
01:21:35,767 --> 01:21:41,397
And someone sneakin' around the corner

1448
01:21:41,481 --> 01:21:47,028
Could that be old Mack the Knife?

1449
01:21:47,695 --> 01:21:50,573
There's a tug boat

1450
01:21:50,656 --> 01:21:53,159
Down by the river, don't cha know

1451
01:21:54,202 --> 01:21:55,203
(EXHALES)

1452
01:21:55,286 --> 01:21:58,498
Where a cement bag's
just a-drooping on down

1453
01:21:58,581 --> 01:22:00,625
- (SONG FADES)
- (TENSE GRAND MUSIC PLAYING)

1454
01:22:06,130 --> 01:22:08,091
(SHIP MOTOR WHIRRING)

1455
01:22:10,802 --> 01:22:11,803
(GUN FIRING QUIETLY)

1456
01:22:12,553 --> 01:22:14,555
(SAILORS SPEAKING IN GERMAN)

1457
01:22:40,373 --> 01:22:41,374
(RUSTLING)

1458
01:22:41,457 --> 01:22:42,458
- (GUN FIRES QUIETLY)
- (GRUNTS)

1459
01:22:44,585 --> 01:22:46,045
(SOLDIER SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

1460
01:22:46,129 --> 01:22:47,130
Not yet.

1461
01:22:47,672 --> 01:22:49,924
(SOLDIERS CLEARING THROAT,
CLAMORING)

1462
01:22:50,800 --> 01:22:51,801
Mein Herr.

1463
01:22:54,929 --> 01:22:56,889
(IN GERMAN)

1464
01:22:58,516 --> 01:22:59,642
Haysey...

1465
01:22:59,725 --> 01:23:00,893
(GUN FIRING QUIETLY)

1466
01:23:00,977 --> 01:23:02,895
(GUS LAUGHING)

1467
01:23:02,979 --> 01:23:05,940
(SINGING IN GERMAN)

1468
01:23:07,441 --> 01:23:09,026
(CROWD GASPS, CHEERS)

1469
01:23:16,617 --> 01:23:18,619
(TENSE GRAND
MUSIC CRESCENDOS)

1470
01:23:19,453 --> 01:23:20,872
- (MUSIC FADES)
- (SINGING CONTINUES MUTEDLY)

1471
01:23:25,042 --> 01:23:26,878
(SPEAKING IN GERMAN)

1472
01:23:32,175 --> 01:23:33,634
(INTENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

1473
01:23:47,398 --> 01:23:48,608
HENRY: (IN ENGLISH) Up there
on the left, sir.

1474
01:23:48,691 --> 01:23:49,692
GUS: Yes.

1475
01:23:50,193 --> 01:23:51,277
- (GUN FIRES QUIETLY)
- (SOLDIER SCREAMS)

1476
01:23:51,360 --> 01:23:52,987
- (CRASHES)
- (GUS LAUGHS)

1477
01:23:53,487 --> 01:23:54,488
He made a crash!

1478
01:23:54,572 --> 01:23:56,282
(SOLDIER SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

1479
01:23:59,410 --> 01:24:01,245
(SPEAKS GERMAN)

1480
01:24:04,207 --> 01:24:05,416
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)
- (SOLDIERS GROAN)

1481
01:24:05,499 --> 01:24:07,376
- (SOLDIER SHOUTS IN GERMAN)
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)

1482
01:24:09,378 --> 01:24:12,006
We could take that car, sir.
Save us some shoe leather.

1483
01:24:16,886 --> 01:24:18,262
(GRUNTS)

1484
01:24:21,474 --> 01:24:23,100
(CONTINUES SINGING)

1485
01:24:23,184 --> 01:24:24,810
(INTENSE MUSIC CONTINUES)

1486
01:24:27,104 --> 01:24:28,356
(SINGING MUTEDLY)

1487
01:24:46,332 --> 01:24:48,876
(SINGING AUDIBLY IN ENGLISH)
Look out, old Macky is back

1488
01:24:48,960 --> 01:24:50,670
- (MUSIC STOPS)
- (INDISTINCT CONVERSATION)

1489
01:24:50,753 --> 01:24:53,005
(IN GERMAN)

1490
01:24:56,550 --> 01:24:58,427
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)
- (THUD)

1491
01:25:08,521 --> 01:25:09,522
(VEHICLE APPROACHING)

1492
01:25:10,982 --> 01:25:12,024
MAN: (IN ENGLISH) Incoming.

1493
01:25:15,319 --> 01:25:16,320
(ENGINE STOPS)

1494
01:25:18,990 --> 01:25:20,658
(DOORS OPEN, CLOSE)

1495
01:25:20,741 --> 01:25:22,743
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

1496
01:25:26,372 --> 01:25:27,498
Papers please.

1497
01:25:28,499 --> 01:25:30,459
- Commander. (EXHALES)
- All good, Freddy?

1498
01:25:30,543 --> 01:25:32,712
Charges are set to go
once we're out of the harbor, sir.

1499
01:25:34,505 --> 01:25:35,506
Let's carry on then.

1500
01:25:36,007 --> 01:25:37,842
(DRAMATIC CHORD PLAYS)

1501
01:25:37,925 --> 01:25:39,885
(SOLDIERS SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

1502
01:25:41,429 --> 01:25:42,430
(GEOFFREY EXHALES)

1503
01:25:48,561 --> 01:25:50,563
(HEINRICH SPEAKING GERMAN)

1504
01:25:51,188 --> 01:25:52,690
MARJORIE: Did you enjoy your gift?

1505
01:25:53,566 --> 01:25:54,567
HEINRICH: Mmm.

1506
01:25:56,819 --> 01:26:03,826
I think now it's time
that the fox shows his den to the vixen.

1507
01:26:05,995 --> 01:26:07,747
(TENSE MUSIC CONTINUES)

1508
01:26:12,376 --> 01:26:13,794
- (GUS GRUNTS)
- (GUN FIRES QUIETLY)

1509
01:26:13,878 --> 01:26:14,962
(SOLDIER THUDS)

1510
01:26:15,046 --> 01:26:16,797
- (CHOKING)
- (GUS GRUNTS)

1511
01:26:33,689 --> 01:26:35,149
- (SOLDIERS CHEERING, LAUGHING)
- (UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

1512
01:26:38,194 --> 01:26:40,571
Heron, why are the lights still on?

1513
01:26:41,906 --> 01:26:43,240
I lit the room with oil lamps,

1514
01:26:43,324 --> 01:26:45,201
so they wouldn't notice
when the power went out.

1515
01:26:47,745 --> 01:26:49,538
(PEOPLE CHEERING, LAUGHING)

1516
01:26:52,208 --> 01:26:53,209
(LOCK CLICKS)

1517
01:26:55,961 --> 01:26:57,254
(SCREAMS)

1518
01:26:57,338 --> 01:26:59,048
- (SAILOR SHOUTING IN GERMAN)
- (ARROW SWOOSHING)

1519
01:27:05,888 --> 01:27:07,556
- (SAILOR SHOUTING IN GERMAN)
- (GUNSHOTS)

1520
01:27:08,641 --> 01:27:10,684
(GEOFFREY PANTING)

1521
01:27:12,186 --> 01:27:13,396
(GRENADE CLATTERS)

1522
01:27:16,315 --> 01:27:18,317
- (ALARM BLARING)
- (SAILORS CLAMORING)

1523
01:27:25,533 --> 01:27:27,493
- (GUNSHOTS)
- (SAILORS SCREAM)

1524
01:27:27,576 --> 01:27:29,120
- Look out!
- (GUNSHOTS)

1525
01:27:30,413 --> 01:27:31,539
(GUN FIRING QUIETLY)

1526
01:27:31,622 --> 01:27:32,873
- (SCREAMS)
- (SAILORS CLAMORING)

1527
01:27:34,083 --> 01:27:35,084
(SAILOR YELLS)

1528
01:27:43,092 --> 01:27:44,510
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)
- (SOLDIER GROANS)

1529
01:27:46,887 --> 01:27:49,932
Freddy, rig this 88,
then take the first tug with Haysey.

1530
01:27:53,436 --> 01:27:54,979
- Gute nacht.
- Guten a bend.

1531
01:27:55,563 --> 01:27:56,689
(SOLDIER 1 GROANING)

1532
01:28:00,651 --> 01:28:01,652
GUS: Guten a bend.

1533
01:28:01,735 --> 01:28:03,487
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)
- (SOLDIER 2 SCREAMS)

1534
01:28:13,372 --> 01:28:15,708
- (SPEAKS GERMAN)
- (BOTH GRUNTING)

1535
01:28:15,791 --> 01:28:17,960
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)
- (SAILOR 1 SCREAMS)

1536
01:28:22,965 --> 01:28:24,425
(CHOKING)

1537
01:28:27,970 --> 01:28:28,971
GUS: (IN ENGLISH) Terribly sorry, old boy.

1538
01:28:29,054 --> 01:28:30,514
- Do you mind? I seem to...
- (KNIFE CLANGS)

1539
01:28:30,598 --> 01:28:33,017
- (CHOKES)
- ...have misplaced my knife.

1540
01:28:33,100 --> 01:28:34,226
(GROANS)

1541
01:28:34,310 --> 01:28:36,061
(ALARM CONTINUES BLARING)

1542
01:28:36,645 --> 01:28:37,855
(CHOKING)

1543
01:28:39,273 --> 01:28:40,316
(LASSEN GRUNTING)

1544
01:28:41,650 --> 01:28:43,194
(SAILOR YELLING IN GERMAN)

1545
01:28:45,571 --> 01:28:46,822
(GROANS)

1546
01:28:49,742 --> 01:28:50,910
- (GUNSHOTS)
- (ADEDAYO SCREAMS)

1547
01:28:50,993 --> 01:28:52,244
(GUN FIRING QUIETLY)

1548
01:28:52,912 --> 01:28:54,997
- (SAILOR 1 SPEAKING GERMAN)
- (ADEDAYO YELLS)

1549
01:28:57,124 --> 01:28:58,250
(SAILOR 2 GRUNTING)

1550
01:29:00,169 --> 01:29:02,087
- (SAILOR 3 YELLS)
- (SAILOR 4 GASPS)

1551
01:29:02,171 --> 01:29:04,548
(SAILOR 5 SHOUTS
IN GERMAN, GROANS)

1552
01:29:05,424 --> 01:29:06,884
(SAILOR 6 YELLS)

1553
01:29:12,723 --> 01:29:14,141
(GRUNTING)

1554
01:29:14,225 --> 01:29:15,601
(SAILOR 7 SHOUTS IN GERMAN)

1555
01:29:18,020 --> 01:29:19,355
(CHOKES)

1556
01:29:19,438 --> 01:29:20,856
(TENSE MUSIC CONTINUES)

1557
01:29:20,940 --> 01:29:22,024
- (SAILOR SPEAKS GERMAN)
- (GUN FIRES QUIETLY)

1558
01:29:22,107 --> 01:29:24,068
- (CLAMORING IN GERMAN)
- (GUN FIRES QUIETLY)

1559
01:29:24,151 --> 01:29:25,319
(SAILOR 1 GRUNTS)

1560
01:29:27,863 --> 01:29:29,365
(SAILOR 2 YELLING)

1561
01:29:29,949 --> 01:29:32,034
- (SAILOR 3 SCREAMING)
- (SLASHING)

1562
01:29:32,117 --> 01:29:33,869
- (SHOUTING IN GERMAN)
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)

1563
01:29:37,373 --> 01:29:38,958
- (GUNSHOT)
- Bugger!

1564
01:29:40,084 --> 01:29:42,169
(CLAMORING)

1565
01:29:46,257 --> 01:29:47,258
Thank you, Billy.

1566
01:29:49,885 --> 01:29:51,053
(BOTH SHOUTING)

1567
01:29:53,722 --> 01:29:54,890
(SAILORS SPEAKING GERMAN)

1568
01:29:55,849 --> 01:29:57,643
- Oh!
- (LASSEN GRUNTS)

1569
01:29:57,726 --> 01:29:59,144
(SAILOR 1 SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

1570
01:29:59,228 --> 01:30:01,021
(SCREAMING, GASPING)

1571
01:30:01,605 --> 01:30:02,856
(SAILOR 2 YELLING)

1572
01:30:04,525 --> 01:30:05,526
(SAILOR 3 ROARS)

1573
01:30:06,318 --> 01:30:08,195
(GASPING)

1574
01:30:08,696 --> 01:30:09,697
- (THUDS)
- (PANTING)

1575
01:30:09,780 --> 01:30:11,782
(FAINT CLAMORING)

1576
01:30:12,366 --> 01:30:13,409
(KNIFE CLANGS)

1577
01:30:17,788 --> 01:30:19,790
(TENSE MUSIC CONTINUES)

1578
01:30:19,873 --> 01:30:21,750
(BOTH GRUNTING)

1579
01:30:25,588 --> 01:30:27,214
(ADEDAYO YELLS, GRUNTS)

1580
01:30:30,384 --> 01:30:32,344
(GRUNTING, YELLING)

1581
01:30:42,605 --> 01:30:43,606
(MUSIC FADES)

1582
01:30:48,944 --> 01:30:49,945
(DOOR CLICKS)

1583
01:30:54,033 --> 01:30:55,743
I hope that's not your blood, Lassen.

1584
01:30:56,827 --> 01:30:57,870
I hope so too.

1585
01:30:58,454 --> 01:31:00,414
(SOLDIERS CLAMORING IN GERMAN)

1586
01:31:00,497 --> 01:31:02,082
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)
- (SAILORS GROAN, THUD)

1587
01:31:03,292 --> 01:31:04,418
(MAN GRUNTS)

1588
01:31:04,918 --> 01:31:07,588
Okay, boys, cast off.
Let's get this ship out of here.

1589
01:31:10,758 --> 01:31:12,217
(GUS SIGHS)

1590
01:31:15,387 --> 01:31:18,891
(IN ENGLISH) Go on. Go on...

1591
01:31:19,475 --> 01:31:20,809
Go on!

1592
01:31:24,563 --> 01:31:26,607
LASSEN: There's three
more rooms just like this one.

1593
01:31:27,274 --> 01:31:29,735
That should stop the U-boats
for the next six months.

1594
01:31:31,445 --> 01:31:32,696
Let's get this thing towed out of here.

1595
01:31:32,780 --> 01:31:34,448
NDULUE: We are here, boys.

1596
01:31:34,531 --> 01:31:36,367
Quietly. Let's set a warning.

1597
01:31:42,247 --> 01:31:45,417
I need you to go to the front of the boat
and attach the Vulcan to the Duchessa,

1598
01:31:45,501 --> 01:31:46,669
Lassen and I will head to the bridge.

1599
01:31:46,752 --> 01:31:48,754
Okay. (SPEAKING YORUBA)

1600
01:31:50,255 --> 01:31:51,256
(IN ENGLISH) Take the right side.

1601
01:31:52,132 --> 01:31:53,967
And you, get up there
and get this thing started.

1602
01:32:06,647 --> 01:32:07,648
It's Gus.

1603
01:32:09,108 --> 01:32:10,275
GEOFFREY: Everyone's in place.

1604
01:32:13,153 --> 01:32:14,405
What,

1605
01:32:14,488 --> 01:32:16,407
you didn't actually think
it would work, did you?

1606
01:32:17,449 --> 01:32:18,534
It was your plan.

1607
01:32:19,493 --> 01:32:21,870
Well, let's make sure
we keep our end of the bargain.

1608
01:32:22,454 --> 01:32:23,997
Signal back and I'll heave off.

1609
01:32:26,542 --> 01:32:27,710
So, what happens now?

1610
01:32:28,335 --> 01:32:30,003
We wait for the anchor chain to blow.

1611
01:32:30,087 --> 01:32:31,672
When do we expect that to happen?

1612
01:32:31,755 --> 01:32:33,716
- (MOTOR WHIRRING)
- Shortly, I hope.

1613
01:32:33,799 --> 01:32:35,259
And then we're free to take her.

1614
01:32:36,009 --> 01:32:40,139
However, the real race begins
once the fuel depot goes.

1615
01:32:40,639 --> 01:32:43,016
Then we'll have every soldier
on the island turning up.

1616
01:32:45,018 --> 01:32:47,479
We don't wanna be around to witness that.

1617
01:32:48,731 --> 01:32:51,442
How long was that fuse
you attached to the anchor chain?

1618
01:32:52,609 --> 01:32:53,861
We'll find out soon enough.

1619
01:32:53,944 --> 01:32:55,112
(ALARM BLARING FAINTLY)

1620
01:32:55,195 --> 01:32:56,905
ADEDAYO: Wait for it,
you're gonna catch the rope.

1621
01:32:56,989 --> 01:32:58,741
(MEN CLAMORING IN YORUBA)

1622
01:33:01,618 --> 01:33:02,995
(GRUNTING)

1623
01:33:07,207 --> 01:33:08,208
(DRAMATIC CHORD PLAYS)

1624
01:33:08,292 --> 01:33:09,293
(IN ENGLISH) Come on.

1625
01:33:10,753 --> 01:33:12,171
(WHIRS, CLICKS)

1626
01:33:14,173 --> 01:33:16,258
- (FAINT EXPLOSION)
- (PEOPLE GASP)

1627
01:33:17,176 --> 01:33:18,761
(CLAMORING)

1628
01:33:21,305 --> 01:33:22,306
(LOCK RATTLING)

1629
01:33:25,726 --> 01:33:27,686
(BAND PLAYING SWING MUSIC)

1630
01:33:29,188 --> 01:33:30,606
First domino falls.

1631
01:33:32,399 --> 01:33:33,942
- Hitch up the other line.
- Yes, boss.

1632
01:33:34,026 --> 01:33:35,027
Pick up the slack.

1633
01:33:37,070 --> 01:33:39,531
FREDDY: They need to move her
before the fuel dump blows.

1634
01:33:40,824 --> 01:33:42,367
Heron, we need Marjorie.

1635
01:33:42,451 --> 01:33:44,411
Leave Marjorie to me.

1636
01:33:44,495 --> 01:33:45,788
We'll catch you up.

1637
01:33:46,705 --> 01:33:47,706
Very good.

1638
01:33:48,290 --> 01:33:49,541
Let's go!

1639
01:33:49,625 --> 01:33:51,126
(MUSIC FADES)

1640
01:34:03,639 --> 01:34:05,265
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

1641
01:34:33,877 --> 01:34:35,629
HEINRICH: I have to say, Fraulein,

1642
01:34:38,173 --> 01:34:39,174
you were good.

1643
01:34:40,551 --> 01:34:42,177
And you were sly.

1644
01:34:43,387 --> 01:34:45,138
There are only two types of people

1645
01:34:45,222 --> 01:34:47,391
that are as sly as the fox.

1646
01:34:48,350 --> 01:34:52,020
The German and the Jew.

1647
01:34:55,148 --> 01:34:59,111
And you are not German.

1648
01:35:00,279 --> 01:35:01,947
I think now it's time...

1649
01:35:02,030 --> 01:35:03,824
(MUSIC BUILDS)

1650
01:35:03,907 --> 01:35:05,951
- ...for a real party.
- (LIGHTER CLICKS)

1651
01:35:06,034 --> 01:35:07,578
(MUSIC FADES)

1652
01:35:16,128 --> 01:35:18,714
That wasn't supposed to happen yet.

1653
01:35:18,797 --> 01:35:20,173
- (FAINT EXPLOSIONS)
- (CHAINS RATTLING)

1654
01:35:23,468 --> 01:35:24,761
Shackle her!

1655
01:35:25,512 --> 01:35:26,513
And follow me.

1656
01:35:27,556 --> 01:35:29,308
(SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

1657
01:35:30,183 --> 01:35:31,602
The harbor is under attack!

1658
01:35:31,685 --> 01:35:33,270
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

1659
01:35:33,353 --> 01:35:35,355
(ALL CLAMORING)

1660
01:35:39,693 --> 01:35:41,695
(INTENSE WESTERN MUSIC PLAYING)

1661
01:35:42,571 --> 01:35:44,489
(BINEA IN GERMAN)

1662
01:35:44,573 --> 01:35:45,782
(CLAMORING)

1663
01:35:45,866 --> 01:35:47,743
(ALARM WAILING)

1664
01:35:50,037 --> 01:35:51,455
(FAINT SHOUTING)

1665
01:35:52,080 --> 01:35:53,081
GUS: They're coming.

1666
01:35:58,211 --> 01:35:59,588
We need power on the engine.

1667
01:36:02,424 --> 01:36:03,842
(ENGINE ACCELERATING)

1668
01:36:03,926 --> 01:36:06,345
- She's too heavy!
- Pick up the slack!

1669
01:36:07,262 --> 01:36:08,263
(GRUNTS)

1670
01:36:10,098 --> 01:36:12,392
(SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

1671
01:36:15,812 --> 01:36:16,813
(COCKS GUN)

1672
01:36:18,023 --> 01:36:19,024
GUS: (IN ENGLISH) Wait...

1673
01:36:19,608 --> 01:36:21,610
(SOLDIER 1 IN GERMAN)

1674
01:36:21,693 --> 01:36:23,612
(SOLDIER 2 SHOUTING
INDISTINCTLY)

1675
01:36:23,695 --> 01:36:24,696
FREDDY: (IN ENGLISH) She's not moving!

1676
01:36:26,281 --> 01:36:28,742
SOLDIER 3: Fire! Fire! Fire!

1677
01:36:28,825 --> 01:36:29,910
GUS: Wait for it.

1678
01:36:29,993 --> 01:36:32,329
(GUNSHOTS)

1679
01:36:34,206 --> 01:36:36,625
(CLAMORING)

1680
01:36:40,128 --> 01:36:41,713
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)
- (GASPS)

1681
01:36:42,965 --> 01:36:44,341
(SOLDIERS SCREAMING)

1682
01:36:46,760 --> 01:36:48,136
(SOLDIER 4 SHOUTS INDISTINCTLY)

1683
01:36:48,220 --> 01:36:49,221
(SOLDIER 5 YELLS)

1684
01:36:50,847 --> 01:36:52,641
We need more power on the engine.

1685
01:36:52,724 --> 01:36:55,060
Give me more power! More power!

1686
01:36:55,143 --> 01:36:56,603
(ENGINE ACCELERATES HARDER)

1687
01:36:56,687 --> 01:36:58,146
That's it, it's working!

1688
01:36:59,106 --> 01:37:00,273
- (ENGINE PULSES)
- That's it!

1689
01:37:00,357 --> 01:37:02,359
(ADVENTUROUS WESTERN
MUSIC PLAYING)

1690
01:37:06,989 --> 01:37:08,031
(OFFICER IN GERMAN)

1691
01:37:09,116 --> 01:37:10,200
- (CLAMORING CONTINUES)
- (GUNSHOTS)

1692
01:37:16,581 --> 01:37:18,500
(YELLING)

1693
01:37:20,502 --> 01:37:22,004
(SOLDIER SCREAMING)

1694
01:37:27,467 --> 01:37:28,635
NDULUE: (IN ENGLISH) Ready!

1695
01:37:33,181 --> 01:37:34,433
(MACHINE GUN FIRING)

1696
01:37:36,435 --> 01:37:37,561
(SOLDIERS SCREAMING)

1697
01:37:39,521 --> 01:37:41,064
- (BOTH GRUNTING)
- (GUN FIRES)

1698
01:37:46,153 --> 01:37:47,821
(SOLDIER SCREAMING)

1699
01:37:48,655 --> 01:37:49,906
(SCREAMS)

1700
01:37:49,990 --> 01:37:51,616
- (MOUTHING) Haysey!
- (TENSE MUSIC BUILDING)

1701
01:37:51,616 --> 01:38:21,616
<b>Subtitle | www.movieddl.me</b>

1702
01:38:31,323 --> 01:38:32,741
- (EXPLOSION)
- (SCREAM)

1703
01:38:32,824 --> 01:38:34,409
(SOLDIERS CLAMORING)

1704
01:38:39,790 --> 01:38:41,041
(OFFICER IN GERMAN)

1705
01:38:45,670 --> 01:38:46,671
(MUSIC SLOWS)

1706
01:38:49,800 --> 01:38:51,301
(FAINT CLAMORING)

1707
01:38:51,384 --> 01:38:53,261
(IN ENGLISH) We're out of range now.

1708
01:38:55,055 --> 01:38:56,098
- I'm no expert.
- (HENRY GROANING)

1709
01:38:56,181 --> 01:38:58,725
But you've got a big old hole
in your shoulder, Haysey.

1710
01:38:59,351 --> 01:39:00,894
(SOLDIERS SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

1711
01:39:03,188 --> 01:39:04,689
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

1712
01:39:07,442 --> 01:39:09,611
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)
- (SOLDIERS GROAN)

1713
01:39:12,197 --> 01:39:14,199
(SOLDIERS CLAMORING)

1714
01:39:15,408 --> 01:39:17,410
(OFFICER SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

1715
01:39:21,164 --> 01:39:23,333
(SOLDIERS SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

1716
01:39:34,511 --> 01:39:36,972
(OFFICER IN SPANISH)

1717
01:39:47,107 --> 01:39:48,108
(IN ENGLISH) Captain,

1718
01:39:48,859 --> 01:39:51,236
would you explain to me
what's going on here?

1719
01:39:52,445 --> 01:39:53,613
The power is gone.

1720
01:39:54,489 --> 01:39:56,741
The fuel depot has been sabotaged.

1721
01:39:56,825 --> 01:39:59,119
And no one knows what's happening.
But this is your fault.

1722
01:39:59,202 --> 01:40:00,704
Where is my ship?

1723
01:40:02,330 --> 01:40:03,957
The Duchessa, where did it go?

1724
01:40:04,040 --> 01:40:06,334
Someone's taken him
while you weren't looking.

1725
01:40:07,419 --> 01:40:08,712
You idiot!

1726
01:40:08,795 --> 01:40:12,215
You always have to say something
at the very wrong time.

1727
01:40:13,258 --> 01:40:16,136
There is never a right time with you!

1728
01:40:17,012 --> 01:40:18,180
Your greed and perversion

1729
01:40:18,263 --> 01:40:20,473
has distracted you from your duties.

1730
01:40:20,557 --> 01:40:22,100
Now my harbor is destroyed.

1731
01:40:22,184 --> 01:40:23,810
And my ship is gone!

1732
01:40:27,314 --> 01:40:30,358
And now you're gone too. Thank you.

1733
01:40:30,442 --> 01:40:31,610
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

1734
01:40:44,998 --> 01:40:46,208
(EXPLOSION)

1735
01:40:55,091 --> 01:40:57,469
(TENSE MUSIC PLAYS)

1736
01:40:58,470 --> 01:40:59,596
(IN ENGLISH) Impressive.

1737
01:41:02,515 --> 01:41:03,767
HENRY: Sounds like your detonators worked.

1738
01:41:03,850 --> 01:41:05,018
(BOTH LAUGHING)

1739
01:41:11,608 --> 01:41:12,609
(SIGHS)

1740
01:41:15,070 --> 01:41:17,072
(FAINT CLAMORING)

1741
01:41:21,034 --> 01:41:22,953
(TENSE MUSIC CONTINUES)

1742
01:41:23,578 --> 01:41:25,247
(OFFICER SPEAKS GERMAN)

1743
01:41:29,834 --> 01:41:31,586
(SOLDIERS SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

1744
01:41:31,670 --> 01:41:32,671
(MUSIC FADES OUT)

1745
01:41:40,929 --> 01:41:42,222
Chapeau, mademoiselle.

1746
01:41:42,889 --> 01:41:46,476
(IN ENGLISH) You play well.
You really are the vixen.

1747
01:41:47,769 --> 01:41:48,812
Am I?

1748
01:41:50,605 --> 01:41:52,565
Well, my hand's been revealed.

1749
01:41:55,902 --> 01:41:57,946
So, what now?

1750
01:41:58,530 --> 01:42:01,241
Now, I possess your hand

1751
01:42:02,242 --> 01:42:04,452
and for everything you have done to me,

1752
01:42:05,620 --> 01:42:09,040
I will visit a thousand fold upon you.

1753
01:42:09,124 --> 01:42:11,084
(IN GERMAN)

1754
01:42:13,837 --> 01:42:15,046
(CHAINS CLANG)

1755
01:42:16,464 --> 01:42:17,465
(IN ENGLISH) Yeah.

1756
01:42:20,302 --> 01:42:21,303
(COCKS GUN)

1757
01:42:24,806 --> 01:42:25,849
But no.

1758
01:42:36,151 --> 01:42:38,320
- (SOLDIER SHOUTS)
- (GUN FIRING QUIETLY)

1759
01:42:39,362 --> 01:42:41,072
- (DOOR OPENS)
- Lie down.

1760
01:42:44,826 --> 01:42:47,829
Gus, we can't wait much longer.

1761
01:42:51,207 --> 01:42:52,500
They're coming.

1762
01:42:52,584 --> 01:42:54,002
If we stay here,

1763
01:42:54,085 --> 01:42:56,087
we'll lose contact with the others.

1764
01:42:56,171 --> 01:42:57,339
Hold fast, Billy.

1765
01:42:58,131 --> 01:43:00,091
Heron has a way of surviving and Marjorie,

1766
01:43:00,884 --> 01:43:03,553
well... good luck with that.

1767
01:43:08,600 --> 01:43:10,602
That's a patrol boat coming towards us.

1768
01:43:15,023 --> 01:43:16,941
- Gus, we need to leave. Now.
- (COCKS GUN)

1769
01:43:17,901 --> 01:43:19,235
Hold on...

1770
01:43:27,911 --> 01:43:29,829
(BOAT APPROACHING)

1771
01:43:31,539 --> 01:43:32,540
It's them.

1772
01:43:33,917 --> 01:43:35,460
KAMBILl: RH.

1773
01:43:36,336 --> 01:43:38,546
- KB.
- GUS: Marjorie.

1774
01:43:38,630 --> 01:43:41,091
Overdressed and under dressed
at the same time.

1775
01:43:43,927 --> 01:43:45,720
Come on, let's get you
out of those shackles.

1776
01:43:49,516 --> 01:43:51,393
(STATIC CRACKLING)

1777
01:43:51,476 --> 01:43:52,685
Come in, Violet.

1778
01:43:53,353 --> 01:43:54,896
Calling HMS Violet.

1779
01:43:56,189 --> 01:43:57,357
Come in, Violet.

1780
01:43:57,440 --> 01:43:58,817
GEOFFREY: (ON RADIO) This is Maid Honor.

1781
01:43:58,900 --> 01:44:00,068
Go ahead, Maid Honor.

1782
01:44:00,902 --> 01:44:02,278
- Loudspeaker.
- (CLICKS)

1783
01:44:02,362 --> 01:44:04,406
GEOFFREY: Sorry to bother you
at this time of the night,

1784
01:44:04,489 --> 01:44:07,200
but we've found ourselves with one or two
items that might be of interest to you.

1785
01:44:08,493 --> 01:44:10,203
Shall we rendezvous for a handover?

1786
01:44:11,704 --> 01:44:13,123
Get me Admiral Pound.

1787
01:44:13,206 --> 01:44:15,125
(TENSE ADVENTUROUS
MUSIC PLAYING)

1788
01:44:21,005 --> 01:44:22,173
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

1789
01:44:23,049 --> 01:44:24,384
- Yes?
- GUBBINS: (ON PHONE) Sir,

1790
01:44:24,467 --> 01:44:26,845
- good news and bad news.
- Yes, yes. Get to it.

1791
01:44:26,928 --> 01:44:28,638
Bad news, they didn't sink her.

1792
01:44:29,431 --> 01:44:32,308
Good news, they stole her.

1793
01:44:33,685 --> 01:44:35,937
Congratulations, Prime Minister.

1794
01:44:36,020 --> 01:44:37,939
(TENSE ADVENTUROUS
MUSIC CONTINUES)

1795
01:45:00,336 --> 01:45:01,337
(MUSIC FADES OUT)

1796
01:45:01,421 --> 01:45:02,672
(MEN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

1797
01:45:04,048 --> 01:45:05,133
OFFICER: Hold it there!

1798
01:45:06,384 --> 01:45:07,469
Commander.

1799
01:45:07,552 --> 01:45:10,388
You were ordered by Admiral Pound
to cease activities.

1800
01:45:10,472 --> 01:45:11,473
You did not.

1801
01:45:12,265 --> 01:45:15,643
Therefore, you are to be returned
to England to face a tribunal. You.

1802
01:45:16,311 --> 01:45:19,230
Return to your tug
with the rest of your militia.

1803
01:45:19,731 --> 01:45:21,107
- Take them to the brig.
- OFFICER: Sir!

1804
01:45:21,191 --> 01:45:23,943
Good to see you too, Commander.

1805
01:45:24,027 --> 01:45:25,737
Separate cells.

1806
01:45:25,820 --> 01:45:27,155
OFFICER: Follow me!

1807
01:45:27,864 --> 01:45:29,407
Let's go! Let's get moving!

1808
01:45:31,117 --> 01:45:32,660
- RH.
- KB.

1809
01:45:32,744 --> 01:45:33,745
SAILOR: Come on.

1810
01:45:35,205 --> 01:45:36,414
Go on, move.

1811
01:45:36,498 --> 01:45:37,540
One moment, seaman.

1812
01:45:40,251 --> 01:45:41,711
(CURIOUS WESTERN MUSIC PLAYING)

1813
01:45:41,794 --> 01:45:42,795
Billy.

1814
01:45:45,215 --> 01:45:46,674
One eye on the boundary...

1815
01:45:48,009 --> 01:45:49,385
One eye on the pub.

1816
01:45:51,179 --> 01:45:52,889
They'll thank you for this one day.

1817
01:45:53,765 --> 01:45:56,809
I'm not sure that's what we were
really looking for, was it,

1818
01:45:57,936 --> 01:45:58,937
Your Highness?

1819
01:46:00,855 --> 01:46:03,525
Shop's open for you anytime, Major.

1820
01:46:14,285 --> 01:46:17,413
GLORIA: Sorry to intrude, Prime Minister,
but M thought you should see this.

1821
01:46:22,961 --> 01:46:23,962
CHURCHILL: Thank you, Gloria.

1822
01:46:24,712 --> 01:46:25,713
(MUSIC TURNS HAPPY)

1823
01:46:30,760 --> 01:46:32,428
(MAN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

1824
01:46:34,264 --> 01:46:36,766
- (GATE RATTLING)
- GUARD: Line up. Face front!

1825
01:46:37,976 --> 01:46:40,562
Line up. Face front!

1826
01:46:40,645 --> 01:46:42,814
Line up. Face front!

1827
01:46:42,897 --> 01:46:44,148
No need to shout.

1828
01:46:47,318 --> 01:46:48,403
GUARD: Stand still!

1829
01:46:49,153 --> 01:46:50,905
Any chance of a cup of tea?

1830
01:46:51,864 --> 01:46:53,157
You, back up to the wall.

1831
01:46:53,241 --> 01:46:54,534
Off the cloth, moth.

1832
01:46:55,827 --> 01:46:56,828
GUARD: Stand straight!

1833
01:46:57,787 --> 01:46:58,788
(DOOR OPENS)

1834
01:46:58,871 --> 01:47:00,957
- (FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)
- (WALKING STICK CLACKING)

1835
01:47:08,047 --> 01:47:10,174
CHURCHILL: Never before
have the senior Military

1836
01:47:10,258 --> 01:47:12,594
and Navy Commanders of this country

1837
01:47:12,677 --> 01:47:14,429
been so united in their condemnation.

1838
01:47:15,179 --> 01:47:18,224
It is their view that the discipline

1839
01:47:18,308 --> 01:47:20,518
on which our armed forces depends

1840
01:47:20,602 --> 01:47:23,938
has been undermined
by men serving no master

1841
01:47:24,022 --> 01:47:27,400
but their own thirst
for blood, murder and mayhem.

1842
01:47:29,068 --> 01:47:32,739
Men who disobeyed a direct order
from the Admiral of the fleet himself,

1843
01:47:34,365 --> 01:47:38,077
and chose instead
to trust the whim and intuition

1844
01:47:39,287 --> 01:47:40,997
of the man standing beside him.

1845
01:47:42,749 --> 01:47:44,083
How dare they.

1846
01:47:46,502 --> 01:47:47,795
When only this morning,

1847
01:47:48,963 --> 01:47:52,300
the first American soldiers
arrived on British soil,

1848
01:47:52,383 --> 01:47:54,886
ready to stand shoulder to shoulder
with us in Europe.

1849
01:47:56,429 --> 01:47:58,806
Allies who risked death
crossing the North Atlantic,

1850
01:48:00,391 --> 01:48:02,268
and only by some miracle

1851
01:48:03,978 --> 01:48:07,690
found their crossing
untroubled by Nazi U-boats.

1852
01:48:09,942 --> 01:48:12,195
A happy circumstance, I might add,

1853
01:48:13,363 --> 01:48:14,906
which cannot be accounted for,

1854
01:48:15,490 --> 01:48:18,201
but which has cleared the way
for the United States

1855
01:48:18,284 --> 01:48:20,203
to enter the European war.

1856
01:48:20,286 --> 01:48:21,788
And for which I know

1857
01:48:21,871 --> 01:48:25,792
President Roosevelt
to be immeasurably grateful.

1858
01:48:29,420 --> 01:48:32,882
But setting aside
this stroke of unexplained fortune,

1859
01:48:33,800 --> 01:48:37,261
what is to be done
with this unruly company

1860
01:48:37,345 --> 01:48:38,596
who do not obey orders?

1861
01:48:38,680 --> 01:48:44,143
Who seem to have formed their own
ministry of ungentlemanly warfare.

1862
01:48:44,227 --> 01:48:45,978
(CURIOUS WESTERN MUSIC PLAYING)

1863
01:48:48,856 --> 01:48:50,817
From now on, they work for me.

1864
01:48:53,027 --> 01:48:54,570
(MUSIC TURNS WHIMSICAL)

1865
01:49:03,621 --> 01:49:04,622
(MUSIC FADES OUT)

1866
01:49:05,581 --> 01:49:07,583
(CAPTIVATING MUSIC PLAYING)

1867
01:50:29,999 --> 01:50:32,001
(AMUSING WESTERN MUSIC PLAYING)

1868
01:53:29,345 --> 01:53:30,346
(MUSIC FADES OUT)

1869
01:53:30,888 --> 01:53:32,890
(EXCITING MUSIC PLAYING)

1870
01:55:54,115 --> 01:55:56,075
(EXCITING MUSIC CONTINUES)

1871
01:56:24,770 --> 01:56:26,772
(TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

1872
01:58:00,366 --> 01:58:02,368
(CURIOUS GENTLE MUSIC PLAYING)

1873
02:00:00,527 --> 02:00:01,528
(MUSIC FADES OUT)

